# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: e1-series-boat-racing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/2024-e1-series-championship] The **2024 UIM E1 World Championship** was the inaugural season of the E1 Series electric powerboat racing series.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/2024-e1-series-championship] The season launched on 2 February in Jeddah, Saudi Arabia.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/2024-e1-series-championship] Team Brady were crowned as the champions on October 29th.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/2024-e1-series-championship] The season was originally supposed to begin in 2023, with a goal to have about one race per month.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/2024-e1-series-championship] A need for more teams caused delays to the start, with the first calendar being officially released on June 8, 2023.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/2024-e1-series-championship] The provisional calendar had the first race set to take place during January 2024 in Jeddah, Saudi Arabia, with the season finale in Rotterdam, Netherlands in September 2024.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/2024-e1-series-championship] On December 20, 2023, a new calendar was released, which saw the series expand to three regions (Europe, the Middle East, and Asia), with the premiere getting pushed back to February.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/2024-e1-series-championship] This version also featured a race in Geneva, Switzerland, which has since been removed from the calendar.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/2024-e1-series-championship] On June 26, 2024, a race was announced for Lake Como, which replaced Rotterdam as the location of the fifth round.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/2024-e1-series-championship] On October 29th, 2024, Team Brady was announced as the champions, ending the season early and forgoing the planned Hong Kong race.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/2024-e1-series-championship] The following events were on the original calendar, but did not appear in the final version.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/2024-e1-series-championship] A race weekend consists of testing, free practice, and qualifying on the first day, while the semi-finals, play-off race, eliminator race, place race, and finals all take place on the second day.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/2024-e1-series-championship] The first race in Jeddah featured a modified format, as there were only 8 teams.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/2024-e1-series-championship] For rounds 2–6, the format was changed to accommodate the extra entry of Westbrook Racing, which brought the total number of teams up to 9.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/2024-e1-series-championship] Qualifying is three sets of three racers, with each team getting two sessions in order to allow both pilots to set a time.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/2024-e1-series-championship] After qualifying, the teams are split into three groups of 3, racing against each other in 6 semi-final races.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/2024-e1-series-championship] The top team in each group automatically goes to the final, while the second-place finishers battle in a Playoff race for the last spot.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/2024-e1-series-championship] The third-place finishers race in an Eliminator race, with the last-place finisher placing 9th for the event.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/2024-e1-series-championship] The bottom two teams in the Playoff, and the top two teams in the Eliminator then compete in the Place Race, for positions 5 through 9.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/2024-e1-series-championship] The top four teams compete in the Final, which consists of the combined results of Super Final 1 and Super Final 2.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/2024-e1-series-championship] The UIM E1 Pilot Academy was created to train a new generation of racers to compete in the E1 Series.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/2024-e1-series-championship] Female and male athletes with experience in motorsport, cycling, Esports, extreme sports and high-speed sports were invited to apply.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/2024-e1-series-championship] A total of 34 racers took part in the training, with 18 being selected to compete in the inaugural season of the series.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/2024-e1-series-championship] Team Miami led the qualifying on day 1, earning an extra point in the championship.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/2024-e1-series-championship] In the semifinals, Team Brady and Team Rafa topped their respective groups, while Team Miami and Team Blue Rising also qualified for the final.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/2024-e1-series-championship] Super Final 1 was led by Team Rafa, followed by Team Miami and Team Brady.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/2024-e1-series-championship] In Super Final 2, spray blocked Team Rafa's Cris Lazarraga's view, causing her to cut a corner and take an additional long lap as a penalty.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/2024-e1-series-championship] Sam Coleman took the lead of Super Final 2, and clinched the overall final for Team Brady.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/2024-e1-series-championship] Team Miami claimed their second consecutive pole position, while Team Blue Rising failed to set a qualifying time, and both Team Rafa and Aoki Racing Team had one of their session's lap times disqualified.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/2024-e1-series-championship] Team Brazil, Team Drogba, and newcomers Westbrook Racing were the three seminfinal winners, earning an automatic spot in the final.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/2024-e1-series-championship] Team Brady won the play-off race to clinch the fourth spot in the finals, while Team Checo lost the eliminator race and was therefore out of the place race.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/2024-e1-series-championship] Team Brady had a dominant showing, winning Super Final 1 and 2 to earn their second victory in the series.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/2024-e1-series-championship] Choppy waters at the third event shook up the standings.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/2024-e1-series-championship] Team Drogba claimed pole position, while two-time winners Team Brady were eliminated after a power outage in Semifinal 3.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/2024-e1-series-championship] Team Blue Rising clinched fourth place overall, but had to withdraw from Super Final 2 after the nose of their craft detached while racing in Super Final 1.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/2024-e1-series-championship] The same thing happened to Team Brazil in Super Final 2, while Westbrook Racing stalled mid-race but crossed the finish line in second and picked up an extra point for the fastest lap.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/2024-e1-series-championship] Team Miami won their first final, and moved to first in the standings.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/2024-e1-series-championship] Husband and wife duo Ieva Millere-Hagin and Stefan Hagin subbed in for Team Checo and Team Brazil, respectively.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/2024-e1-series-championship] Team Brazil faced issues with their RaceBird during the weekend, ending in last place.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/2024-e1-series-championship] Team Rafa claimed their first pole position and first semi-finals win, while Team Brady returned to the top step of the podium, despite taking second in both finals races.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/2024-e1-series-championship] Team Aoki and Team Checo both received yellow cards for dangerous driving, the first of the season.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/2024-e1-series-championship] Team Westbrook took their first finals victory, as Lucas Ordóñez won Super Final 1.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/2024-e1-series-championship] Team Brady's Emma Kimiläinen damaged her left foil when she hit a buoy in Super Final 2, which meant Sara Price's second-place finish clinched the victory for Westbrook.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/2024-e1-series-championship] An additional point is given to the fastest team in qualifying, and the team with the fastest lap.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/2024-e1-series-championship] For the first race, because there were only 8 teams, the point system was slightly different.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/alejandro-agag] Agag was born in Madrid to an Algerian-Belgian father, Youssef Agag, who was a banker, and a Spanish mother, Soledad Longo Álvarez de Sotomayor.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/alejandro-agag] There, he went to Colegio Retamar, Pozuelo de Alarcón, a fee-paying school affiliated with Opus Dei, a Catholic movement.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/alejandro-agag] Agag graduated from the Colegio Universitario de Estudios Financieros (CUNEF) in Madrid with a degree in economics and business studies.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/alejandro-agag] In 1989, Agag joined Nuevas Generaciones (NNGG), the youth organization of the main centre-right Spanish party Partido Popular, which at the time was in the opposition.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/alejandro-agag] He joined the international relations department due to his knowledge of multiple languages.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/alejandro-agag] During that time, Agag traveled extensively, representing NNGG in organizations such as the Democrat Youth Community of Europe and EYCD.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/alejandro-agag] Agag was elected International Secretary of NNGG at their congress in 1994.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/alejandro-agag] In the same year, Agag graduated from university and became Deputy Secretary General of the European People's Party (EPP), an offer that was a direct result of the election of the German Klaus Welle as Secretary General a few months earlier.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/alejandro-agag] As Deputy Secretary General, Agag was tasked with coordinating different groups within the EPP and drafting policy papers to be presented at the congress.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/alejandro-agag] Agag was a member of the EPP Summit, which includes all of EPP's heads of state and government.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/alejandro-agag] Also during that year, Agag ran for a seat in the European Parliament, but did not win.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/alejandro-agag] In 1996, the centre-right won the elections in Spain, and Agag became the political aide of the prime minister at the time, José María Anzar.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/alejandro-agag] In 1999, he was elected a member of the European Parliament for the Partido Popular.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/alejandro-agag] He entered the Economic and Monetary Affairs Commission, focusing on antitrust policy.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/alejandro-agag] The next year, he led the Parliament's report on antitrust policy and was active in redrafting that policy.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/alejandro-agag] Also in 2000, he was elected Secretary General of the European People's Party, replacing his colleague, Klaus Welle.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/alejandro-agag] During his mandate as Secretary General, the organization expanded to Eastern Europe.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/alejandro-agag] During that period, it incorporated more than 20 new political parties from that region.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/alejandro-agag] Later that year, for the first time, the EPP won the European Parliament elections and became the largest political force in Europe.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/alejandro-agag] Making a controversial decision against some member parties of the EPP, he pushed for the acceptance of Forza Italia, Silvio Berlusconi's party, into the organization.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/alejandro-agag] Berlusconi went on to win the 2001 Italian elections.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/alejandro-agag] In 2000, Agag was elected to be the Secretary General of the Christian Democratic International in Mexico, now known as Centrist Democratic International.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/alejandro-agag] In 2001, Agag made a decision to cease his political activities in order to further his career in business and sporting activities.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/alejandro-agag] The following year he was succeeded as Secretary General of the EPP by Antonio López-Istúriz.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/alejandro-agag] He remained a member of the European Parliament until 2002.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/alejandro-agag] In 2002, Agag moved to London and started his own consultancy firm.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/alejandro-agag] Agag founded a company called Addax Capital LLP, which is regulated by the FSA.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/alejandro-agag] Agag is currently Chairman of Addax and was joined in 2009 by Ignacio Muñoz Alonso, former CEO of Rothschild Bank in Spain.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/alejandro-agag] GQ Magazine named him the Spanish Businessman of the Year in 2008.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/alejandro-agag] Agag's business activity within sports mainly focuses on motorsport and football.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/alejandro-agag] According to the Spanish newspaper *El País*, Agag and Flavio Briatore acquired the Formula One T.V. rights in Spain.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/alejandro-agag] Agag owned the Barwa Addax GP2 Series Team, which won the title in 2008 and was runner-up in 2009.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/alejandro-agag] He took over the team from former F1 driver Adrián Campos in mid-2007.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/alejandro-agag] The team's main sponsor was the Qatari real estate company Barwa.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/alejandro-agag] In 2010, the Addax GP3 Team competed in the GP3 Series.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/alejandro-agag] Through his connection within the sport, Agag has worked with Flavio Briatore, Bernie Ecclestone and Lakshmi Mittal.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/alejandro-agag] Together, they bought the English football club Queens Park Rangers (QPR) in 2007.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/alejandro-agag] Agag was chairman of QPR for a few months during the takeover and then remained in the club as a shareholder.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/alejandro-agag] QPR was promoted to the English Premier League in 2011.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/alejandro-agag] He is chairman of the Formula E Championship, an electric car racing series.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/alejandro-agag] The inaugural season began in September 2014 and lasted until June 2015.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/alejandro-agag] On 5 September 2002, Agag married Ana Aznar Botella, the daughter of then-prime minister José María Aznar and politician Ana Botella, at El Escorial in Madrid.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/alejandro-agag] Guests included King Juan Carlos I and Queen Sofia of Spain.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/alejandro-agag] Former British Prime Minister Tony Blair and Italian Prime Minister Silvio Berlusconi served as witnesses.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/alejandro-agag] Agag is fluent in Spanish, English, French, and Italian.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] Delevingne started her acting career with a minor role in the 2012 film adaptation of *Anna Karenina* by Joe Wright.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] Her most notable roles include Margo Roth Spiegelman in the romantic mystery film *Paper Towns* (2015), the Enchantress in the comic book film *Suicide Squad* (2016), and Laureline in Luc Besson's *Valerian and the City of a Thousand Planets* (2017).
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] Cara Jocelyn Delevingne was born on 12 August 1992, in Hammersmith, London, the daughter of property developer Charles Hamar Delevingne and Pandora Stevens Delevingne.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] She has two older sisters, Chloe and Poppy, and a paternal half-brother, Alexander Jaffe.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] Her maternal grandfather was the publishing executive and English Heritage chairman Jocelyn Stevens.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] Her paternal grandmother was Angela Delevingne and her maternal grandmother was Jane Armyne Sheffield, a granddaughter of Lionel Faudel-Phillips, 3rd Baronet.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] Delevingne has 16 godparents, including the actress Joan Collins and the Eton College provost and former Condé Nast International president Nicholas Coleridge.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] Her paternal grandaunt was the notorious courtesan Doris Delevingne.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] Delevingne grew up in Belgravia and from 2003 to 2009 attended Bedales School.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] She found school challenging because of her dyspraxia and depression.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] In 2009, she left school and signed as a model with Storm Management.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] Delevingne has abused multiple illegal drugs since her adolescence, including 'a lot of' cannabis, LSD 'every day', ketamine, Xanax, GBL 'every day', GHB, and cocaine.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] She also dealt illegal drugs during her adolescence.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] In 2022, after her 30th birthday, Delevingne participated in a rehab program and has maintained sobriety since then.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] Delevingne had her first modelling job at age ten, in an editorial for *Vogue Italia*.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] While continuing with Burberry, she appeared in runway shows in Paris, Milan and New York, for all of the major fashion brands of the day.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] From then on, she was much sought-after, and formed what would become a long-lasting relationship with Chanel's Karl Lagerfeld.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] In 2012, Delevingne was featured in the Victoria's Secret Fashion Show.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] In 2013, Delevingne appeared in a collaboration between Katie Grand and Tod's and sang "I Want Candy"' in their mini-film *Gang*.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] Delevingne was also featured in Chanel's Cruise show in Singapore.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] In 2015, Delevingne became more selective with the shows she appeared in, due to both her growing acting career and a turn away from work as a sole marker of success.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] Off the runway, Delevingne has made numerous commercials and appeared in product ads for Chanel, Dior, Marc Jacobs, Burberry,DKNY, Tag Heuer, Penshoppe, Pepe Jeans, Alexander Wang, YSL, and Mango, among others.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] In 2016, she became one of the faces of Rimmel.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] Delevingne's magazine covers include *Vogue*, *V*, *British GQ*, *Vogue Paris*, *Elle UK*, *Elle Australia*, *The Wall Street Journal*,, *Love*, *The Edit*, and *Glamour*.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] Delevingne played her first film role as Princess Sorokina in the 2012 adaptation of *Anna Karenina*.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] In August 2013, Delevingne voiced a DJ of a pop radio station in the video game *Grand Theft Auto V*.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] Delevingne went on to play the part of Melanie in the British psychological thriller film *The Face of an Angel*.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] The film received mixed reviews, but some critics commended Delevingne's performance.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] On 24 October 2014, she starred in a sketch for an annual 90-minute comedy TV event called *The Feeling Nuts Comedy Night*.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] A month later, she featured in Die Antwoord's music video for their song "Ugly Boy".
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] Then in December 2014, Delevingne starred in *Reincarnation*, a short film by Karl Lagerfeld for Chanel.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] In June 2014, Delevingne made her TV debut opposite veteran British actress Sylvia Syms in the final episode of *Playhouse Presents.* This was a series of self-contained TV plays, made by British broadcaster Sky Arts.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] In February 2015, Delevingne appeared in ASAP Ferg's music video for his song *Dope Walk.* Later in May 2015, she was also in Taylor Swift's star studded "Bad Blood" music video which went on to break Vevo's 24-hour viewing record, with 20.1 million views in its day of release.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] Delevingne co-starred in the adaptation of John Green's novel *Paper Towns* (2015) as Margo Roth Spiegelman.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] The film brought in $12,650,140 on the opening weekend in the US, which placed it 6th at the box office.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] Delevingne played a mermaid in the 2015 fantasy film *Pan*.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] In 2016, Delevingne co-starred as Enchantress, a villainess with magical abilities, in *Suicide Squad*, an action film based on the DC comic book series of the same name.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] The film was released to generally negative reviews, although it was a box office success.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] Delevingne's performance received mixed reviews from critics.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] The film *Kids in Love*, a British coming of age drama, was released in 2016.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] The cast includes many up and coming young actors, with Will Poulter and Alma Jodorowsky as lead roles alongside Sebastian de Souza and Delevingne who plays the role of Viola.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] Delevingne starred, alongside Dane DeHaan and Rihanna, in the Luc Besson film *Valerian and the City of a Thousand Planets*, an adaptation of the comic book series *Valérian and Laureline*.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] The film began shooting in December 2015, and was released in July 2017.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] Delevingne plays Annetje in the period romance film *Tulip Fever*.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] She also plays the role of Kath Talent in the film *London Fields*, based on the 1989 novel of the same name by Martin Amis.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] The Amazon Prime Video fantasy steampunk series *Carnival Row* features Delevingne in the female lead role (opposite Orlando Bloom) as Vignette Stonemoss, a faerie war refugee.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] In 2022, she joined the cast of *Only Murders in the Building* for its second season.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] Delevingne sings and plays the drums and guitar.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] In 2011 and 2012, Delevingne wrote and recorded two albums under artist manager Simon Fuller and was offered a record deal but turned down the offer because her name would be changed.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] In 2013, she recorded an acoustic duet cover version of *Sonnentanz* with British soul and jazz singer-songwriter Will Heard.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] Delevingne teamed up with Pharrell Williams to make the song "CC the World", which was used for the short Chanel film *Reincarnation* in which both Pharrell and Delevingne star.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] This was released to the public on 1 December 2014.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] The duo performed the song before a live audience for the Chanel show at the Park Avenue Armory in New York City in March 2015.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] On 28 July 2017, Delevingne released the music video for her song "I Feel Everything" from *Valerian and the City of a Thousand Planets*.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] Delevingne's background vocals are featured on the song "Pills" from the 2017 studio album, *Masseduction*, by American musician St.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] Vincent, whom Delevingne previously dated from 2014 to 2016.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] Her backing vocals are featured on the title track of Fiona Apple's 2020 album, *Fetch the Bolt Cutters*.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] In September 2025, Delevingne's name was included on the lineup for the Primavera Sound 2026 music festival, despite that she had not released any new songs.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] In April 2026, Delevingne announced an upcoming eleven-date debut musical tour, which began in Berlin on June 1 2026 and will end in Brooklyn on June 26 2026.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] She will also perform at All Things Go Music Festival in New York City on September 25, 2026.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] On May 29, 2026, Delevingne signed with Warner Records and released two new songs, "I Forgot" and "Out of My Head", accompanied by a short film directed by Jessica Lee Gagné, and it was announced that her debut album would be released in summer 2026.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] In 2017, Delevingne made her debut as a novelist of young adult literature with her book *Mirror, Mirror*, which contains an LGBT theme and was co-written with British writer Rowan Coleman.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] In 2020, Delevingne and her sisters launched Della Vite, a line of vegan Prosecco.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] In December 2022, Delevingne featured in her series *Planet Sex* for BBC Three, shown over six episodes, exploring sexuality including her own, in various worldwide locations.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] From 11 March 2024, Delevigne will make her stage debut taking over as Sally Bowles in the West End musical *Cabaret* at the Kit Kat Club (Playhouse Theatre) opposite Luke Treadaway as the Emcee for 12 weeks.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] Delevingne has designed two fashion collections for DKNY and Mulberry.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] Her DKNY capsule collection featured a variety of sporty street style items ranging from beanie hats to leather jackets.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] DKNY described the collection as "mostly unisex".
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] The collection took approximately two years from the first announcement to when it was released on 15 October 2014.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] Delevingne has also designed four collections for Mulberry featuring rucksacks and handbags.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] The collection also consisted of purses, iPad sleeves, phone covers, zipped pouches, and passport holders.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] The fourth and latest collection was released 3 June 2015.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] Delevingne's naturally thick eyebrows are considered her signature look, and she has been credited with popularising bold eyebrows as a beauty trend of the 2010s.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] Delevingne was named by the *Evening Standard* as one of London's "1,000 Most Influential People of 2011", in the category Most Invited.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] In 2013, the *Evening Standard* also ranked her 20th on their "Power 1000" list "because of her domination of the catwalks at London Fashion Week and her huge social media following".
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] The same year, Delevingne was the most googled fashion figure and the most re-blogged model on Tumblr.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] In March 2014, Delevingne was included in *The Sunday Times Magazine*'s "100 Makers of the 21st Century" list of influential British people.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] Later that year, she was ranked sixth on the "World's Highest-Paid Models" list by *Forbes*, earning an estimated US$3.5 million (£2.7 million).
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] By 2015, she had moved up to second on this list, earning $9 million (£7 million).
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] Delevingne has appeared twice in categories run by *AskMen*, ranking at number 13 on their "Top 99 Most Desirable Women" list in 2014, and at number 40 on their "Crush List: Top 99 Women" in 2016.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] She also briefly appeared on Martin Brundle's grid walk for the 2023 British Grand Prix, where she denied Brundle an interview, claiming that she "can't hear anything", in an attempt to get out of the interview.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] Delevingne is lesbian, which she publicly revealed in 2026, after having previously identified as pansexual.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] In June 2015, she confirmed that she was in a relationship with American musician St.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] In May 2018, Delevingne came out as genderfluid.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] In June 2019, she confirmed that she was in a relationship with actress and model Ashley Benson.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] In April 2020, the couple split after two years of dating.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] Delevingne has been dating musician Leah Mason, also known as Minke, since 2022.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] In June 2026, Delevingne revealed at *The Louis Theroux Podcast* that she was "entangled" with Amber Heard, her co-star in *London Fields*, following Heard's divorce from Johnny Depp.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] Delevingne is a self-described animal lover.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] Following the killing of Cecil the lion in 2015, she auctioned off her personal TAG Heuer watch in aid of wildlife conservation, raising £18,600 for WildCRU.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] She founded EcoResolution, an environmental justice platform with Advaya and has given speeches about climate change and supported stronger environmental regulation.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] She co-created at least one short story comic in *The Most Important Comic Book on Earth: Stories to Save the World*, which was released on 28 October 2021 by DK.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] At the Women in the World summit in October 2015, Delevingne spoke about her battle with depression, which began at age 15, when she discovered her mother's drug addiction.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] The following year, she left school for six months and agreed to go on medication, which she said may have saved her life.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] In 2017, on *This Morning*, she revealed that she also has ADHD.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] In October 2017, Delevingne alleged that circa 2016, producer Harvey Weinstein sexually harassed her, attempted to kiss her without consent, and propositioned her for a threesome in a hotel room in exchange for a role.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] Despite declining, she was still cast in the film, but says she regretted it because his actions terrified her.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] The Weinstein Company produced the 2017 film *Tulip Fever*, which starred Delevingne.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] She also alleges that circa 2014, he told her she would never work as an actress in Hollywood because of her sexuality.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] In a March 2023 interview with *Vogue*, Delevingne said that she had checked herself into rehab in late 2022 and entered a twelve-step program, and had been sober since then.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] Her first tattoo was a lion on her finger, representing her zodiac sign of Leo.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] She has a tattoo of her lucky number, the Roman numeral XII, on her side under her right arm, and "MADE IN ENGLAND" on the sole of her left foot.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] She has said that her most important tattoo is the elephant on her right arm, in memory of her late grandmother.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] In the early hours of 15 March 2024, Delevingne's home in Studio City, Los Angeles, caught fire.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] Ninety-four firefighters from the city of Los Angeles responded to the call but the property was declared a total loss.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] A firefighter and a person who was in the house were injured, and Delevingne's two cats made it out alive; Delevingne was not at the mansion at the time of the fire.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/cara-delevingne] The following day, it was revealed that the cause of the fire was most likely "electrical".
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Croatian history began with the 6th century arrival of the Croats to Roman Illyria.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Settled as two duchies a century later, Croatia was granted independence in 878 under Duke Branimir and elevated into a kingdom under King Tomislav in 925.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The Trpimirović dynastic succession crisis placed Croatia into a personal union with Hungary in 1102.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] In 1527, amid Ottoman conflict, Croatia aligned with the Habsburg monarchy.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] It reorganized into the State of Slovenes, Croats, and Serbs before merging into the Kingdom of Yugoslavia in 1918.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] During World War II, most of Croatia was invaded by the Axis powers who installed a puppet state known as the Independent State of Croatia.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] A resistance movement restored sovereignty, emerging as the Socialist Republic of Croatia within the Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia in 1943.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Croatia declared independence from Yugoslavia in 1991, successfully fighting the War of Independence until 1995.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Modern Croatia is a representative democracy with a prime minister, president, and unicameral parliament.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Its constitution ensures separation of powers between the executive, legislative, and judicial branches.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Croatian politics reflect a multi-party system.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Croatia is part of many international organizations and forums including the European Union, United Nations, WTO, and NATO, among others.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] It exerts regional influence as a small power in Europe, particularly within neighboring Southeast Europe.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Since 1999, the Croatian Armed Forces have deployed internationally for a variety of peacekeeping missions and military interventions.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Croatia was elected to serve on the non-permanent seat of the UN Security Council from 2008 to 2009.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] A developed country, Croatia has an advanced economy considered high-income and dominated by its service, industrial, and agricultural sectors.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Its tourism sector is prominent, generating significant economic activity across the country.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Croatia has heavily invested in infrastructure, especially in transport routes and facilities along European corridors.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] An emerging energy power in Europe, it has strategic investments in liquefied natural gas, geothermal networks, and electric transport.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] It has extensive biodiversity, wildlife, and natural resources across its geography.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Croatia provides social security, universal health care, and subsidized primary and secondary education while supporting culture through media and publishing.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Alternate forms are *Khoróatos* and **Khoroúathos**).
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The origin of the ethnonym is uncertain, but most probably is from Proto-Ossetian / Alanian **xurvæt-* or **xurvāt-*, in the meaning of "one who guards" ("guardian, protector").
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The presumably oldest stone inscription with fully preserved ethnonym is the 9th-century Branimir inscription found near Benkovac, where Duke Branimir is styled *Dux Cruatorvm*, likely dated between 879 and 892, during his rule.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The Latin term **Chroatorum** is attributed to a charter of Duke Trpimir I of Croatia, dated to 852 in a 1568 copy of a lost original, but it is not certain if the original was found to be older than the Branimir inscription.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The area known as modern Croatia was inhabited throughout the prehistoric period.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Neanderthal fossils dating to the middle Palaeolithic period were unearthed in northern Croatia, best presented at the Krapina site.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Remnants of Neolithic and Chalcolithic cultures were found in all regions.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The largest proportion of sites is in the valleys of northern Croatia.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The most significant are Baden, Starčevo, and Vučedol cultures.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Iron Age hosted the early Illyrian Hallstatt culture and the Celtic La Tène culture.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The region of modern-day Croatia was settled by Illyrians and Liburnians, while the first Greek colonies were established on the islands of Hvar, Korčula, and Vis.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] In 9 AD, the territory of today's Croatia became part of the Roman Empire.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Emperor Diocletian was native to the region.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] He had a large palace built in Split, to which he retired after abdicating in AD 305.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] During the 5th century, the last de jure Western Roman Emperor Julius Nepos ruled a small realm from the palace after fleeing Italy in 475.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The Roman period ends with Avar and Croat invasions in the late 6th and first half of the 7th century and the destruction of almost all Roman towns.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Roman survivors retreated to more favourable sites on the coast, islands, and mountains.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The city of Dubrovnik was founded by such survivors from Epidaurum.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The ethnogenesis of the Croats is a subject of scholarly discussion, reflecting the complexity of early medieval migrations and the integration of diverse populations.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The predominant scholarly consensus, based on historical chronicles, proposes that the White Croats originated as a Slavic group that migrated from White Croatia during the Migration Period.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] According to the work *De Administrando Imperio* written by 10th-century Byzantine Emperor Constantine VII, Croats settled in the Roman province of Dalmatia in the first half of the 7th century after they defeated the Avars.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Although there exist some scholarly disputes about the account's reliability and interpretation, recent archaeological data has established that the migration and settlement of the Slavs/Croats was in the late 6th and early 7th century.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Eventually, a dukedom was formed, Duchy of Croatia, ruled by Borna, as attested by chronicles of Einhard starting in 818.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The record represents the first document of Croatian realms, vassal states of Francia at the time.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Its neighbor to the North was Principality of Lower Pannonia, at the time ruled by duke Ljudevit who ruled the territories between the Drava and Sava rivers, centred from his fort at Sisak.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] This population and territory throughout history was tightly related and connected to Croats and Croatia.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Christianisation of Croats began in the 7th century at the time of archon Porga of Croatia, initially probably encompassed only the elite and related people, but mostly finished by the 9th century.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The Frankish overlordship ended during the reign of Mislav, or his successor Trpimir I.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The native Croatian royal dynasty was founded by duke Trpimir I in the mid 9th century, who defeated the Byzantine and Bulgarian forces.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The first native Croatian ruler recognised by the Pope was duke Branimir, who received papal recognition from Pope John VIII on 7 June 879.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Tomislav was the first king of Croatia, noted as such in a letter of Pope John X in 925.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Tomislav defeated Hungarian and Bulgarian invasions.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The medieval Croatian kingdom reached its peak in the 11th century during the reigns of Petar Krešimir IV (1058–1074) and Dmitar Zvonimir (1075–1089).
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] When Stjepan II died in 1091, ending the Trpimirović dynasty, Dmitar Zvonimir's brother-in-law Ladislaus I of Hungary claimed the Croatian crown.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] This led to a war and personal union with Hungary in 1102 under Coloman.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] For the next four centuries, the Kingdom of Croatia was ruled by the Sabor (parliament) and a Ban (viceroy) appointed by the king.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] This period saw the rise of influential nobility such as the Frankopan and Šubić families to prominence, and ultimately numerous Bans from the two families.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] An increasing threat of Ottoman conquest and a struggle against the Republic of Venice for control of coastal areas ensued.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The Venetians controlled most of Dalmatia by 1428, except the city-state of Dubrovnik, which became independent.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Ottoman conquests led to the 1493 Battle of Krbava field and the 1526 Battle of Mohács, both ending in decisive Ottoman victories.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] King Louis II died at Mohács, and in 1527, the Croatian Parliament met in Cetin and chose Ferdinand I of the House of Habsburg as the new ruler of Croatia, under the condition that he protects Croatia against the Ottoman Empire while respecting its political rights.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Following the decisive Ottoman victories, Croatia was split into civilian and military territories in 1538.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The military territories became known as the Croatian Military Frontier and were under direct Habsburg control.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Ottoman advances in Croatia continued until the 1593 Battle of Sisak, the first decisive Ottoman defeat, when borders stabilised.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] During the Great Turkish War (1683–1698), Slavonia was regained, but western Bosnia, which had been part of Croatia before the Ottoman conquest, remained outside Croatian control.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The present-day border between the two countries is a remnant of this outcome.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Dalmatia, the southern part of the border, was similarly defined by the Fifth and the Seventh Ottoman–Venetian Wars.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The Ottoman wars drove demographic changes.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] During the 16th century, Croats from western and northern Bosnia, Lika, Krbava, the area between the rivers Una and Kupa, and especially from western Slavonia, migrated towards Austria.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Present-day Burgenland Croats are direct descendants of these settlers.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] To replace the fleeing population, the Habsburgs encouraged Bosnians to provide military service in the Military Frontier.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The Croatian Parliament supported King Charles III's Pragmatic Sanction and signed their own Pragmatic Sanction in 1712.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Subsequently, the emperor pledged to respect all privileges and political rights of the Kingdom of Croatia, and Queen Maria Theresa made significant contributions to Croatian affairs, such as introducing compulsory education.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Between 1797 and 1809, the First French Empire increasingly occupied the eastern Adriatic coastline and its hinterland, ending the Venetian and the Ragusan republics, establishing the Illyrian Provinces.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] In response, the Royal Navy blockaded the Adriatic Sea, leading to the Battle of Vis in 1811.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The Illyrian provinces were captured by the Austrians in 1813 and absorbed by the Austrian Empire following the Congress of Vienna in 1815.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] This led to the formation of the Kingdom of Dalmatia and the restoration of the Croatian Littoral to the Kingdom of Croatia under one crown.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The 1830s and 1840s featured romantic nationalism that inspired the Croatian National Revival, a political and cultural campaign advocating the unity of South Slavs within the empire.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Its primary focus was establishing a standard language as a counterweight to Hungarian while promoting Croatian literature and culture.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] During the Hungarian Revolution of 1848, Croatia sided with Austria.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Ban Josip Jelačić helped defeat the Hungarians in 1849 and ushered in a Germanisation policy.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] This is around the time that Nikola Tesla was born in Smiljan.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] By the 1860s, the failure of the policy became apparent, leading to the Austro-Hungarian Compromise of 1867.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The creation of a personal union between the Austrian Empire and the Kingdom of Hungary followed.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The treaty left Croatia's status to Hungary, which was resolved by the Croatian–Hungarian Settlement of 1868 when the kingdoms of Croatia and Slavonia were united.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The Kingdom of Dalmatia remained under de facto Austrian control, while Rijeka retained the status of *corpus separatum* previously introduced in 1779.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] After Austria-Hungary occupied Bosnia and Herzegovina following the 1878 Treaty of Berlin, the Military Frontier was abolished.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The Croatian and Slavonian sectors of the Frontier returned to Croatia in 1881, under provisions of the Croatian–Hungarian Settlement.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Renewed efforts to reform Austria-Hungary, entailing federalisation with Croatia as a federal unit, were stopped by World War I.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] On 29 October 1918, the Croatian Parliament (*Sabor*) declared independence and decided to join the newly formed State of Slovenes, Croats, and Serbs, which in turn entered into union with the Kingdom of Serbia on 4 December 1918 to form the Kingdom of Serbs, Croats, and Slovenes.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The Croatian Parliament never ratified the union with Serbia and Montenegro.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The 1921 constitution defining the country as a unitary state and abolition of Croatian Parliament and historical administrative divisions effectively ended Croatian autonomy.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The new constitution was opposed by the most widely supported national political party—the Croatian Peasant Party (HSS) led by Stjepan Radić.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The political situation deteriorated further as Radić was assassinated in the National Assembly by NRS member, Serbian nationalist politician Puniša Račić in 1928, culminating in King Alexander I's establishment of the 6 January Dictatorship in 1929.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The dictatorship formally ended in 1931 when the king imposed a more unitary constitution.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The HSS, now led by Vladko Maček, continued to advocate federalisation, resulting in the Cvetković–Maček Agreement of August 1939 and the autonomous Banovina of Croatia.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The Yugoslav government retained control of defence, internal security, foreign affairs, trade, and transport while other matters were left to the Croatian Sabor and a crown-appointed Ban.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] In April 1941, Yugoslavia was invaded by Nazi Germany and Fascist Italy.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Following the invasion, a German-Italian installed puppet state named the Independent State of Croatia (NDH) was established.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Most of Croatia, Bosnia and Herzegovina, and the region of Syrmia were incorporated into this state.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Parts of Dalmatia were annexed by Italy, Hungary annexed the northern Croatian regions of Baranja and Međimurje.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The NDH regime was led by Ante Pavelić and the ultranationalist Ustaše, a fringe movement in pre-war Croatia.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] With German and Italian military and political support, the regime introduced racial laws and launched a genocide campaign against Serbs, Jews, and Roma.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Many were imprisoned in concentration camps; the largest was the Jasenovac complex.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Anti-fascist Croats were targeted by the regime as well.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Several concentration camps (most notably the Rab, Gonars and Molat camps) were established in Italian-occupied territories, mostly for Slovenes and Croats.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] At the same time, the Yugoslav Royalist and Serbian nationalist Chetniks pursued a genocidal campaign against Croats and Muslims, aided by Italy.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Nazi German forces committed crimes and reprisals against civilians in retaliation for Partisan actions, such as in the villages of Kamešnica and Lipa in 1944.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] On 22 June 1941, the 1st Sisak Partisan Detachment was formed near Sisak, the first military unit formed by a resistance movement in occupied Europe.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] That sparked the beginning of the Yugoslav Partisan movement, a communist, multi-ethnic anti-fascist resistance group led by Josip Broz Tito.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] In ethnic terms, Croats were the second-largest contributors to the Partisan movement after Serbs.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] In per capita terms, Croats contributed proportionately to their population within Yugoslavia.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] By May 1944 (according to Tito), Croats made up 30% of the Partisan's ethnic composition, despite making up 22% of the population.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The movement grew fast, and at the Tehran Conference in December 1943, the Partisans gained recognition from the Allies.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] With Allied support in logistics, equipment, training and airpower, and with the assistance of Soviet troops taking part in the 1944 Belgrade Offensive, the Partisans gained control of Yugoslavia and the border regions of Italy and Austria by May 1945.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Members of the NDH armed forces and other Axis troops, as well as civilians, were in retreat towards Austria.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Following their surrender, many were killed in the Yugoslav death march of Nazi collaborators.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] In the following years, ethnic Germans faced persecution in Yugoslavia, and many were interned.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The political aspirations of the Partisan movement were reflected in the State Anti-fascist Council for the National Liberation of Croatia, which developed in 1943 as the bearer of Croatian statehood and later transformed into the Parliament in 1945, and AVNOJ—its counterpart at the Yugoslav level.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] In addition, from areas joined to Croatia after the war, a total of 32,000 people died, among whom 16,000 were Italians and 15,000 were Croats.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Approximately 200,000 Croats from the entirety of Yugoslavia (including Croatia) and abroad were killed in total throughout the war and its immediate aftermath, approximately 5.4% of the population.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] After World War II, Croatia became a single-party socialist federal unit of the SFR Yugoslavia, ruled by the Communists, but having a degree of autonomy within the federation.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] In 1967, Croatian authors and linguists published a Declaration on the Status and Name of the Croatian Standard Language demanding equal treatment for their language.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The declaration contributed to a national movement seeking greater civil rights and redistribution of the Yugoslav economy, culminating in the Croatian Spring of 1971, which was suppressed by Yugoslav leadership.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Still, the 1974 Yugoslav Constitution gave increased autonomy to federal units, basically fulfilling a goal of the Croatian Spring and providing a legal basis for independence of the federative constituents.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] At the same time, there was a substantial Croatian diaspora during the Cold War, which included efforts aimed at forming a government in exile.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Following Tito's death in 1980, the political situation in Yugoslavia deteriorated.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] National tension was fanned by the 1986 SANU Memorandum and the 1989 coups in Vojvodina, Kosovo, and Montenegro.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] In January 1990, the Communist Party fragmented along national lines, with the Croatian faction demanding a looser federation.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] In the same year, the first multi-party elections were held in Croatia, while Franjo Tuđman's win exacerbated nationalist tensions.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Some of the Serbs in Croatia left Sabor and declared autonomy of the unrecognised Republic of Serbian Krajina, intent on achieving independence from Croatia.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] As tensions rose, Croatia declared independence on 25 June 1991.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The full implementation of the declaration only came into effect after a three-month moratorium on the decision on 8 October 1991.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] In the meantime, tensions escalated into overt war when the Serbian-controlled Yugoslav People's Army (JNA) and various Serb paramilitary groups attacked Croatia.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] By the end of 1991, a high-intensity conflict fought along a wide front reduced Croatia's control to about two-thirds of its territory.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Serb paramilitary groups then began a campaign of killing, terror, and expulsion of the Croats in the occupied territories, killing thousands of Croat civilians and expelling or displacing as many as 400,000–500,000 Croats and other non-Serbs from their homes.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Serbs living in Croatian towns, especially those near the front lines, were subjected to various forms of discrimination.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Croatian Serbs in Eastern and Western Slavonia and parts of the Krajina were forced to flee or were expelled by Croatian forces, though on a restricted scale and in lesser numbers.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The Croatian Government publicly deplored these practices and sought to stop them, indicating that they were not a part of the Government's policy.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] On 15 January 1992, Croatia gained diplomatic recognition by the European Economic Community, followed by the United Nations.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The war effectively ended in August 1995 with a decisive victory by Croatia; the event is commemorated each year on 5 August as Victory and Homeland Thanksgiving Day and the Day of Croatian Defenders.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Approximately half have returned since then.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Some 19,000 Serb homes were subsequently settled by Croat refugees from Bosnia and Herzegovina.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The remaining occupied areas were restored to Croatia following the Erdut Agreement of November 1995, concluding with the UNTAES mission in January 1998.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Most sources number the war deaths at around 20,000.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] At the turn of the 21st century, Croatia experienced sustained economic growth as the nation democratized but struggled with public corruption and bouts of unemployment.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The Croatian Parliament passed a set of constitutional amendments in November 2000 and March 2001 to convert from a bicameral to a unicameral body, later limiting presidential powers.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Croatia joined the Partnership for Peace in May 2000 and the World Trade Organization in November 2000.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] It joined the military alliance NATO in April 2009.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Adversely impacted by the 2008 financial crisis, austerity measures led to widespread anti-government protests in 2009 and 2011.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] In the latter year, parliament was dissolved in May, with Croatian president Ivo Josipović calling for new elections to quell the protests by December.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] After successfully completing negotiations from 2004 to 2013, Croatia joined the European Union (EU) as its 28th member in July 2013.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Croatia was affected by the 2015 European migrant crisis when Hungary's closure of borders with Serbia pushed over 700,000 refugees and migrants through Croatia.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] On 19 October 2016, Andrej Plenković began serving as the current Croatian Prime Minister.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The most recent presidential elections, held on 12 January 2025, elected Zoran Milanović as president.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] In 2022, Croatia began the process to join the OECD, due to complete membership proceedings by 2026.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The nation joined the Eurozone and Schengen Area in 2023, adopting the euro as its official currency.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Croatia is situated in Central and Southeast Europe, on the coast of the Adriatic Sea.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Hungary is to the northeast, Serbia to the east, Bosnia and Herzegovina and Montenegro to the southeast and Slovenia to the northwest.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] It lies mostly between latitudes 42° and 47° N and longitudes 13° and 20° E.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Part of the territory in the extreme south surrounding Dubrovnik is a practical exclave connected to the rest of the mainland by territorial waters, but separated on land by a short coastline strip belonging to Bosnia and Herzegovina around Neum.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The Pelješac Bridge connects the exclave with mainland Croatia.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The territory covers 56,594 square kilometres (21,851 square miles), consisting of 56,414 square kilometres (21,782 square miles) of land and 128 square kilometres (49 square miles) of water.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] It is the world's 127th largest country.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Elevation ranges from the mountains of the Dinaric Alps with the highest point of the Dinara peak at 1,831 metres (6,007 feet) near the border with Bosnia and Herzegovina in the south to the shore of the Adriatic Sea which makes up its entire southwest border.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Insular Croatia consists of over a thousand islands and islets varying in size, 48 of which are permanently inhabited.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The largest islands are Cres and Krk, each of them having an area of around 405 square kilometres (156 square miles).
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] It is the largest overseas territory on the Adriatic Sea.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The hilly northern parts of Hrvatsko Zagorje and the flat plains of Slavonia in the east which is part of the Pannonian Basin are traversed by major rivers such as Danube, Drava, Kupa, and the Sava.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The Danube, Europe's second longest river, runs through the city of Vukovar in the extreme east and forms part of the border with Vojvodina.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The central and southern regions near the Adriatic coastline and islands consist of low mountains and forested highlands.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Natural resources found in quantities significant enough for production include oil, coal, bauxite, low-grade iron ore, calcium, gypsum, natural asphalt, silica, mica, clays, salt, and hydropower.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Karst topography makes up about half of Croatia and is especially prominent in the Dinaric Alps.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The Plitvice lakes are a system of 16 lakes with waterfalls connecting them over dolomite and limestone cascades.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The lakes are known for their distinctive colours, ranging from turquoise to mint green, grey or blue.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Most of Croatia has a moderately warm and rainy continental climate as defined by the Köppen climate classification.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Mean monthly temperature ranges between −3 °C (27 °F) in January and 18 °C (64 °F) in July.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The coldest parts of the country are Lika and Gorski Kotar featuring a snowy, forested climate at elevations above 1,200 metres (3,900 feet).
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The warmest areas are at the Adriatic coast and especially in its immediate hinterland characterised by Mediterranean climate, as the sea moderates temperature highs.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Consequently, temperature peaks are more pronounced in continental areas.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The lowest temperature of −35.5 °C (−31.9 °F) was recorded on 3 February 1919 in Čakovec, and the highest temperature of 42.8 °C (109.0 °F) was recorded on 4 August 1981 in Ploče.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Mean annual precipitation ranges between 600 millimetres (24 inches) and 3,500 millimetres (140 inches) depending on geographic region and climate type.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The least precipitation is recorded in the outer islands (Biševo, Lastovo, Svetac, Vis) and the eastern parts of Slavonia.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] However, in the latter case, rain occurs mostly during the growing season.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The maximum precipitation levels are observed in the Dinaric Alps, in the Gorski Kotar peaks of Risnjak and Snježnik.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Prevailing winds in the interior are light to moderate northeast or southwest, and in the coastal area, prevailing winds are determined by local features.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Higher wind velocities are more often recorded in cooler months along the coast, generally as the cool northeasterly bura or less frequently as the warm southerly jugo.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The sunniest parts are the outer islands, Hvar and Korčula, where more than 2700 hours of sunshine are recorded per year, followed by the middle and southern Adriatic Sea area in general, and northern Adriatic coast, all with more than 2,000 hours of sunshine per year.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Croatia can be subdivided into ecoregions based on climate and geomorphology.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The country is one of the richest in Europe in terms of biodiversity.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Croatia has four types of biogeographical regions—the Mediterranean along the coast and in its immediate hinterland, Alpine in most of Lika and Gorski Kotar, Pannonian along Drava and Danube, and Continental in the remaining areas.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The most significant are karst habitats which include submerged karst, such as Zrmanja and Krka canyons and tufa barriers, as well as underground habitats.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The country contains three ecoregions: Dinaric Mountains mixed forests, Pannonian mixed forests, and Illyrian deciduous forests.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The karst geology harbours approximately 7,000 caves and pits, some of which are the habitat of the only known aquatic cave vertebrate—the olm.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Forests are abundant, covering 2,490,000 hectares (6,200,000 acres) or 44% of Croatian land area.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Other habitat types include wetlands, grasslands, bogs, fens, scrub habitats, coastal and marine habitats.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] In terms of phytogeography, Croatia is a part of the Boreal Kingdom and is a part of Illyrian and Central European provinces of the Circumboreal Region and the Adriatic province of the Mediterranean Region.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The World Wide Fund for Nature divides Croatia between three ecoregions—Pannonian mixed forests, Dinaric Mountains mixed forests and Illyrian deciduous forests.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Croatia hosts 37,000 known plant and animal species, but their actual number is estimated to be between 50,000 and 100,000.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] More than a thousand species are endemic, especially in Velebit and Biokovo mountains, Adriatic islands and karst rivers.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The most serious threat is habitat loss and degradation.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] A further problem is presented by invasive alien species, especially *Caulerpa taxifolia* algae.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Invasive algae are regularly monitored and removed to protect benthic habitat.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Indigenous cultivated plant strains and domesticated animal breeds are numerous.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] They include five breeds of horses, five of cattle, eight of sheep, two of pigs, and one poultry.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Indigenous breeds include nine that are endangered or critically endangered.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Croatia has 444 protected areas, encompassing 9% of the country.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Those include eight national parks, two strict reserves, and ten nature parks.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The oldest national park in country is Plitvice Lakes National Park, a UNESCO World Heritage Site.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Velebit Nature Park is a part of the UNESCO Man and the Biosphere Programme.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The strict and special reserves, as well as the national and nature parks, are managed and protected by the central government, while other protected areas are managed by counties.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] In 2005, the National Ecological Network was set up, as the first step in the preparation of the EU accession and joining of the Natura 2000 network.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The Republic of Croatia is a unitary constitutional republic using a parliamentary system.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Government powers in Croatia are legislative, executive, and judiciary powers.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The president is the head of state, directly elected to a five-year term and is limited by the constitution to two terms.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] In addition to serving as commander-in-chief of the armed forces, the president has the procedural duty of appointing the prime minister with the parliament and has some influence on foreign policy.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The government is headed by the prime minister, who is supported by deputy prime ministers and various ministers in charge of particular sectors.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] As the executive branch, it is responsible for proposing legislation and a budget, enforcing the laws, and guiding foreign and internal policies.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The government is seated at Banski dvori in Zagreb.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] A unicameral parliament – known as the **Sabor** – holds legislative power.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The number of parliament members can vary from 100 to 160.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] They are elected by popular vote to serve four-year terms.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Legislative sessions take place from 15 January to 15 July, and from 15 September to 15 December annually.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The two largest political parties in Croatia are the Croatian Democratic Union (HDZ) and the Social Democratic Party of Croatia (SDP).
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Croatia has a civil law legal system in which law arises primarily from written statutes, with judges serving as implementers and not creators of law.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Its development was largely influenced by German and Austrian legal systems.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Croatian law is divided into two principal areas—private and public law.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Before EU accession negotiations were completed, Croatian legislation had been fully harmonised with the community acquis.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The main national courts are the Constitutional Court, which oversees violations of the Constitution, and the Supreme Court, which is the highest court of appeal.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] A variety of administrative, commercial, county, misdemeanor, and municipal courts handle cases in their respective domains.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Cases falling within judicial jurisdiction are in the first instance decided by a single professional judge, while appeals are deliberated in mixed tribunals of professional judges.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Lay magistrates also participate in trials.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The State's Attorney Office is the judicial body constituted of public prosecutors empowered to instigate prosecution of perpetrators of offences.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Law enforcement agencies are organised under the authority of the Ministry of the Interior which consist primarily of the national police force.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Croatia's security service is the Security and Intelligence Agency (SOA).
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Croatia has established diplomatic relations with most world nations – 189 states in total – starting with Germany (1991) and most recently with Liberia (2024).
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] It exerts influence as a small power in this region and within European international institutions.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Since the 1990s, Croatia has had unresolved border disputes throughout Southeast Europe, namely with Serbia, Bosnia and Herzegovina, Montenegro, and Slovenia.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] It is a member of the United Nations (UN), the European Union, NATO, the Council of Europe, the Union for the Mediterranean, and the Schengen Area as well as the Eurozone.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Modern Croatian foreign policy objectives include enhancing relations with neighbouring countries, developing international cooperation and promotion of the Croatian economy.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] It supports 57 embassies, 30 consulates and eight permanent diplomatic missions.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The diaspora consists of communities of ethnic Croats and Croatian citizens living outside Croatia.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The largest diaspora is in the United States, with a large population across neighboring Southeast Europe.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The country maintains extensive contact with Croatian communities abroad through administrative and financial support of cultural, sports activities, and economic initiatives.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Croatia actively maintains foreign relations to strengthen and guarantee the rights of the Croatian minority abroad.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The Armed Forces of Croatia (OSRH) consists of three service branches: the Croatian Army, the Croatian Navy and the Croatian Air Force.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] They are headed by the President of Croatia as commander-in-chief while defence policy is overseen by the Government of Croatia.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The military supports the foreign policy of Croatia and international security initiatives.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] It is the sole military wing of the Military Security and Intelligence Agency (VSOA).
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The Armed Forces are spread across continental Croatia and capital city Zagreb, with the Navy largely based in Split.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] According to the 2025 Global Peace Index, Croatia is the 18th most peaceful country in the world.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Since the Croatian War of Independence (1991–1995), the Armed Forces have played a key role in protecting territorial integrity.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The military's first foreign deployment was in 2003 – the War in Afghanistan and Iraq War – later joining the military alliance NATO in 2009.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Croatia maintains a close security and foreign intelligence relationship with NATO and the United States.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The military has been deployed to various United Nations (UN), NATO and American-led missions around the world.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Since joining the European Union (EU) in 2013, it became a part of the EU defence forces.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The Armed Forces have seen significant militarization and modernization since the early 2020s due to regional geopolitical risk.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Its deep integration within Europe and the U.S. has led to modern defence pacts and a robust defence industrial base.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The Croatian military is among the most technologically advanced in Southeast Europe.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Croatia has had military conscription since 2025, previously enacted from 1991 to 2008.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Croatia was first divided into counties in the Middle Ages.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The divisions changed over time to reflect losses of territory to Ottoman conquest and subsequent liberation of the same territory, changes of the political status of Dalmatia, Dubrovnik, and Istria.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The traditional division of the country into counties was abolished in the 1920s when the Kingdom of Serbs, Croats and Slovenes and the subsequent Kingdom of Yugoslavia introduced oblasts and banovinas respectively.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Communist-ruled Croatia, as a constituent part of post-World War II Yugoslavia, abolished earlier divisions and introduced municipalities, subdividing Croatia into approximately one hundred municipalities.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Counties were reintroduced in 1992 legislation, significantly altered in terms of territory relative to the pre-1920s subdivisions.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] In 1918, the Transleithanian part was divided into eight counties with their seats in Bjelovar, Gospić, Ogulin, Osijek, Požega, Varaždin, Vukovar, and Zagreb.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Since 1992, Croatia has been divided into 20 counties and the capital city of Zagreb, the latter having the dual authority and legal status of a county and a city.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] County borders changed in some instances, last revised in 2006.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The counties subdivide into 127 cities and 429 municipalities.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Nomenclature of Territorial Units for Statistics (NUTS) division is performed in several tiers.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] NUTS 1 level considers the entire country in a single unit; three NUTS 2 regions come below that.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Those are Northwest Croatia, Central and Eastern (Pannonian) Croatia, and Adriatic Croatia.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The latter encompasses the counties along the Adriatic coast.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] Individual counties and the city of Zagreb also represent NUTS 3 level subdivision units in Croatia.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] The NUTS local administrative unit (LAU) divisions are two-tiered.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p01] LAU 1 divisions match the counties and the city of Zagreb in effect making those the same as NUTS 3 units, while LAU 2 subdivisions correspond to cities and municipalities.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Croatia has a highly developed mixed economy.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] It is one of the largest economies in Southeast Europe by nominal gross domestic product (GDP).
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] It maintains a similarly high regional GDP-per-capita.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] It is an open economy with accommodative foreign policy, highly dependent on international trade in Europe.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Within Croatia, economic development varies among its counties, with strongest growth in Central Croatia and its financial centre, Zagreb.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] It has a very high level of human development, low levels of income inequality, and a high quality of life.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Croatia's labor market has been perennially inefficient, with an underdeveloped investment climate and an ineffective corporate and income tax system.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Croatia's economic history is closely linked to its historic nation-building efforts.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Its pre-industrial economy leveraged the country's geography and natural resources to guide agricultural growth.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The 1800s saw a shipbuilding boom, railroading, and widespread industrialization.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] During the 1900s, Croatia entered into a planned economy (with socialism) in 1941 and a command economy (with communism) during World War II.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] It experienced rapid urbanization in the 1950s and decentralized in 1965, diversifying its economy before the independence of Croatia in 1990.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The Croatian War of Independence (1991–95) curbed 21–25% of wartime GDP, leaving behind a developing transition economy.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The modern Croatian economy is considered high-income, dominated by its tertiary service and industry sectors which account for 70% of GDP.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Croatia is an emerging energy power in Europe, with strategic investments in liquefied natural gas (LNG), geothermal networks, and electric transport.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] It supports regional economic activity via transportation networks along the Adriatic Sea and throughout Pan-European corridors.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Croatia has free-trade agreements with many world nations and is a part of the World Trade Organization (2000) and the EEA (2013).
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Croatia's largest trading partner was the rest of the European Union, led by Germany, Italy, and Slovenia.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The nation has an emerging defence sector, with major manufacturers including HS Produkt and Đuro Đaković, among others.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Tourism is a major industry and economic sector.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] It has historically represented a large component the country's economic output (GDP), routinely reaching 10% to 15% of total GDP.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Croatia is deeply integrated with the European Union (EU), contributing to overall international tourism in Southeast Europe.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Tourism is concentrated along the Adriatic coast and is strongly seasonal, peaking in July and August.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The most frequented cities are Dubrovnik, Rovinj, Zagreb, Split, Poreč, Umag, and Zadar, respectively.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The history of tourism in Croatia dates back to its time as part of Austria-Hungary when wealthy aristocrats would converge to the sea.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Tourism expanded throughout the 1960s to the 1980s before the independence of Croatia in 1990 curbed tourism until the late-1990s.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The 2000s saw a significant resurgence of Croatian tourism as it underwent nation-building with a particular emphasis on tourism revenue.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] By the late-2000s, Croatia became one of the most visited tourist destinations in the Mediterranean.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] A total of 20.2 million tourists visited Croatia in 2024.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Eight areas in the country have been designated national parks and eleven as nature parks.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] There are ten World Heritage Sites and 116 Blue Flag beaches across the country.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Factors of tourist interest are mainly culture, cuisine, history, fashion, architecture, art, religious sites and routes, nature, maritime access, and nightlife.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Tourism has been partially supported by the Croatian film and television industries due to on-location filming.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Inflation and overtourism has led to increased travel regulations and tourist costs since 2024.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Eurostat estimated that nearly 55% of EU tourist accommodation is between Croatia (117,000) and neighboring Italy (230,000).
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] In 2025, Croatia was the ninth-most-visited state in the EU and third-most-visited in Southern Europe.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The motorway network was largely built in the late 1990s and the 2000s.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] As of December 2020, Croatia had completed 1,313.8 kilometres (816.4 miles) of motorways, connecting Zagreb to other regions and following various European routes and four Pan-European corridors.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The busiest motorways are the A1, connecting Zagreb to Split and the A3, passing east to west through northwest Croatia and Slavonia.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] A widespread network of state roads in Croatia acts as motorway feeder roads while connecting major settlements.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The high quality and safety levels of the Croatian motorway network were tested and confirmed by EuroTAP and EuroTest programmes.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The construction of 2.4-kilometre-long Pelješac Bridge connected the two-halves of Dubrovnik-Neretva County and shortened the route to the Pelješac peninsula and the islands of Korčula and Lastovo by more than 32 km.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The construction of the bridge started in July 2018 after Croatian road operator Hrvatske ceste (HC) signed a 2.08 billion kuna deal for the works with a Chinese consortium led by China Road and Bridge Corporation (CRBC).
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The project was co-financed by the European Union with €357 million.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The construction was completed in July 2022.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Croatia has an extensive rail network spanning 2,604 kilometres (1,618 miles), including 984 kilometres (611 miles) of electrified railways and 254 kilometres (158 miles) of double track railways.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The most significant railways in Croatia are within the Pan-European transport corridors Vb and X connecting Rijeka to Budapest and Ljubljana to Belgrade, both via Zagreb.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] In 2024, the European Investment Bank committed €400 million to support the revitalization of the railway system, focusing on green and digital transformations.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] In July 2024, a significant agreement was signed for the acquisition of six electro-diesel multiple units (EDMUs) to improve connectivity between Split and Zagreb.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Valued at €57.3 million and financed through an EIB loan, this project is part of the broader initiative to modernize Croatia's railway infrastructure.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Airports in Croatia are located and serves Dubrovnik, Osijek, Pula, Rijeka, Split, Zadar, and Zagreb.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The largest and busiest is Franjo Tuđman Airport in Zagreb, followed by Saint Jerome Airport in Split, Ruđer Bošković Airport in Dubrovnik and Zadar Airport in Zadar, with annual passenger numbers exceeding one million respectively.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Croatian airports in terms of passenger arrivals recorded more than 10 million tourists in 2018, 11 million in 2019 and 2023, 13 million in 2024.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Airports in Croatia welcomed more than 14 million passengers in 2025.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] In July 2024, the airline took delivery of its first Airbus A220-300 aircraft, marking the beginning of a transition to a more modern and efficient fleet.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] This initiative includes the acquisition of 13 A220-300 and two A220-100 aircraft, aiming to enhance operational efficiency with 25% lower fuel consumption and reduced emissions.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] As of 2024, Croatia Airlines expanded its international network by introducing direct flights from Zagreb to Tirana, Berlin, and Stockholm.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Additionally, the airline launched services connecting Hamburg to Zagreb starting 1 July 2024.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The busiest cargo seaport is the Port of Rijeka.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The busiest passenger ports are Split and Zadar.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Many minor ports serve ferries connecting numerous islands and coastal cities with ferry lines to several cities in Italy.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The largest river port is port of Vukovar, located on the Danube in Vukovar, representing the nation's outlet to the Pan-European transport corridor VII.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] 610 kilometres (380 miles) of crude oil pipelines serve Croatia, connecting the Rijeka oil terminal with refineries in Rijeka and Sisak, and several transhipment terminals.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The system has a capacity of 20 million tonnes per year.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The natural gas transportation system comprises 2,113 kilometres (1,313 miles) of trunk and regional pipelines, and more than 300 associated structures, connecting production rigs, the Okoli natural gas storage facility, 27 end-users and 37 distribution systems.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Croatia also plays an important role in regional energy security.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The floating liquefied natural gas import terminal off Krk island LNG Hrvatska commenced operations on 1 January 2021, positioning Croatia as a regional energy leader and contributing to diversification of Europe's energy supply.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] In 2010, Croatian energy production covered 85% of nationwide natural gas and 19% of oil demand.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] In 2016, Croatia's primary energy production involved natural gas (24.8%), hydropower (28.3%), crude oil (13.6%), fuelwood (27.6%), and heat pumps and other renewable energy sources (5.7%).
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] In 2017, net total electrical power production reached 11,543 GWh, while it imported 12,157 GWh or about 40% of its electric power energy needs.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Croatia co-owns 50% of the Krško Nuclear Power Plant with neighboring Slovenia.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] This power plant supplies a large part of Croatian imports and provides 15% of the nation's electricity.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] According to Eurostat in 2026, Croatia has the highest quantity of water resources per capita in the EU (30,000 m3).
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] With an estimated population of 3.87 million in 2024, Croatia ranks 128th by population in the world.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Its 2018 population density was 72.9 inhabitants per square kilometre, making Croatia one of the more sparsely populated European countries.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The overall life expectancy in Croatia at birth was 77.7 years in 2024.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The total fertility rate of 1.46 children per mother, is one of the lowest in the world, far below the replacement rate of 2.1; it remains considerably below the high of 6.18 children rate in 1885.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Croatia's death rate has continuously exceeded its birth rate since 1998.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Croatia subsequently has one of the world's oldest populations, with an average age of 45.1 years.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The population rose steadily from 2.1 million in 1857 until 1991, when it peaked at 4.7 million, with the exceptions of censuses taken in 1921 and 1948, i.e., following the world wars.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The natural growth rate is negative with the demographic transition completed in the 1970s.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] In recent years, the Croatian government has been pressured to increase permit quotas for foreign workers, reaching an all-time high of 68.100 in 2019.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] In accordance with its immigration policy, Croatia is trying to entice emigrants to return.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] From 2008 to 2018, Croatia's population dropped by 10%.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Historic demographic shifts are closely tied to Croatia's nation-building efforts and the related 1990s War of Independence.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The war displaced large numbers of the population and emigration increased.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] In 1991, in predominantly occupied areas, more than 400,000 Croats were either removed from their homes by Serb forces or fled the violence.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] During the war's final days, about 150,000–200,000 Serbs fled before the arrival of Croatian forces during Operation Storm.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] After the war, the number of displaced persons fell to about 250,000.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The Croatian government cared for displaced persons via the social security system and the Office of Displaced Persons and Refugees.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Most of the territories abandoned during the war were settled by Croat refugees from Bosnia and Herzegovina, mostly from north-western Bosnia, while some displaced people returned to their homes.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] According to the 2024 Croatian Bureau of Statistics report, 12.5% to 14.6% of Croatia's population were immigrants.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Approximately 4 million Croats live abroad.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Freedom of religion is a constitutional right that protects all religious communities as equal before the law and considers them separate from the state.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] According to the 2021 census, 87.39% of Croatians identify as Christian; of these, Catholics make up the largest group, accounting for 78.97% of the population, after which follows Eastern Orthodoxy (3.32%), Protestantism (0.26%), and other Christians (4.83%).
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The largest religion after Christianity is Islam (1.32%).
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] 4.71% of the population describe itself as non-religious.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] In the Eurostat Eurobarometer Poll of 2010, 69% of the population responded that "they believe there is a God".
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] In a 2009 Gallup poll, 70% answered yes to the question "Is religion an important part of your daily life?" Approximately 24% of the population attend religious services regularly.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Croatian is the official language of the Republic of Croatia and has been an official language of the European Union since Croatia's accession in 2013.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Croatian replaced Latin as the official language of the Croatian government in the 19th century.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Following the Vienna Literary Agreement in 1850, the language and its Latin alphabet underwent reforms to create an unified "Croatian or Serbian" or "Serbo-Croatian" standard, which under various names became the official language of Yugoslavia.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] In SFR Yugoslavia, from 1972 to 1989, the language was constitutionally designated as the "Croatian literary language" and the "Croatian or Serbian language".
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] It was the result of a resistance to and secession from "Serbo-Croatian" in the form of the Declaration on the Status and Name of the Croatian Literary Language as part of the Croatian Spring.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Since gaining independence in the early 1990s, the Republic of Croatia constitutionally designates the language as "Croatian language" and regulates it through linguistic prescription.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The long-standing aspiration for development of its own expressions and thus enrichment of the language, as opposed to the adoption of foreign solutions in the form of loanwords, has been described by linguists as Croatian linguistic purism.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Minority languages are in official use in local government units where more than a third of the population consists of national minorities or where local enabling legislation applies.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Those languages are Czech, Hungarian, Italian, Serbian, and Slovak.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The following minority languages are also recognised: Albanian, Bosnian, Bulgarian, German, Hebrew, Macedonian, Montenegrin, Polish, Romanian, Istro-Romanian, Romani, Russian, Rusyn, Slovene, Turkish, and Ukrainian.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] According to the 2021 Census, 95.25% of citizens declared Croatian as their native language, 1.16% declared Serbian as their native language, while no other language reaches 0.26%.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Croatian is a member of the South Slavic languages and is written using the Latin alphabet.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] There are three major dialects spoken on the territory of Croatia, with standard Croatian based on the Shtokavian dialect.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The Chakavian and Kajkavian dialects are distinguished from Shtokavian by their lexicon, phonology and syntax.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] A 2011 survey revealed that 78% of Croats claim knowledge of at least one foreign language.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] According to a 2005 EC survey, 49% of Croats speak English as the second language, 34% speak German, 14% speak Italian, 10% speak French, 4% speak Russian and 2% speak Spanish.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] However several large municipalities support minority languages.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] A majority of Slovenes (59%) have some knowledge of Croatian.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The country is a part of various language-based international associations, most notably the European Union Language Association.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] is the largest Croatian university and the oldest university in Southeastern Europe.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] As of 2024, the literacy rate in Croatia was 99.45%.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Primary education in Croatia starts at the age of six or seven and consists of eight grades.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] In 2007 a law was passed to increase free, noncompulsory education until 18 years of age.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Compulsory education consists of eight grades of elementary school.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Secondary education is provided by gymnasiums and vocational schools.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] As of the 2022–23 school year, there were 2,073 elementary schools and 738 upper secondary schools in Croatia.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Primary and secondary education are also available in languages of recognised minorities in Croatia, where classes are held in Czech, Hungarian, Italian, Serbian, German and Slovak languages.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] There are 133 elementary and secondary level music and art schools, as well as 83 elementary and 44 secondary schools for disabled children and youth and 11 elementary and 52 secondary schools for adults.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Nationwide leaving exams (Croatian: *državna matura*) were introduced for secondary education students in the school year 2009–2010.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] It comprises three compulsory subjects (Croatian language, mathematics, and a foreign language) and optional subjects and is a prerequisite for university education.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Croatia has eight public universities and two private universities.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The University of Zadar, the first university in Croatia, was founded in 1396 and remained active until 1807, when other institutions of higher education took over until the foundation of the renewed University of Zadar in 2002.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The University of Zagreb, founded in 1669, is the oldest continuously operating university in Southeast Europe.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] There are also 15 polytechnics, of which two are private, and 30 higher education institutions, of which 27 are private.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] In total, there are 131 institutions of higher education in Croatia, attended by more than 160 thousand students.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] In 2022, Croatia's research and development (R&D) expenditure was approximately 1.43% of GDP.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Among the scientific institutes operating in Croatia, the largest is the Ruđer Bošković Institute in Zagreb.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The Croatian Academy of Sciences and Arts in Zagreb is a learned society promoting language, culture, arts and science from its inception in 1866.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Croatia was ranked 40th in the Global Innovation Index in 2025.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The European Investment Bank provided digital infrastructure and equipment to around 150 primary and secondary schools in Croatia.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Twenty of these schools got specialised assistance in the form of gear, software, and services to help them integrate the teaching and administrative operations.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] In 2024, the EIB extended a €207 million loan to the City of Zagreb for infrastructure upgrades, including investments in renewable energy, energy efficiency projects, social and affordable housing, schools, and kindergartens.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Additionally, the EIB signed a €49 million loan with the City of Split to co-finance its 2023–2027 multi-sector investment programme, which includes refurbishing public buildings, increasing energy efficiency, and improving technical equipment for public information and communication.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Croatia has a universal health care system, whose roots can be traced back to the Hungarian-Croatian Parliament Act of 1891, providing a form of mandatory insurance of all factory workers and craftsmen.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The population is covered by a basic health insurance plan provided by statute and optional insurance.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] In 2017, annual healthcare related expenditures reached 22.2 billion kuna (around €3.0 billion).
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Healthcare expenditures make up only 0.6% of private health insurance and public spending.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] In 2022, Croatia spent around 7.2% of its GDP on healthcare.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] In 2025, Croatia ranked 53rd in the world in life expectancy with 75.8 years for men and 81.9 years for women, and it had a low infant mortality rate of 3.3 per 1,000 live births.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] There are hundreds of healthcare institutions in Croatia, including 75 hospitals, and 13 clinics with 23,049 beds.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The hospitals and clinics care for more than 700 thousand patients per year and employ 6,642 medical doctors, including 4,773 specialists.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] There is a total of 69,841 health workers.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] There are 119 emergency units in health centres, responding to more than a million calls.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The principal cause of death in 2022 was cardiovascular disease at 34.3% for men and 43.8% for women, followed by hypertensive disease.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] In 2022 it was estimated that 37% of Croatians are smokers.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] According to 2022 data, 35.65% of the Croatian adult population is obese.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Because of its geographical position, Croatia represents a blend of four different cultural spheres.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] It has been a crossroads of influences from western culture and the east since the schism between the Western Roman Empire and the Byzantine Empire, and also from Central Europe and Mediterranean culture.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The Illyrian movement was the most significant period of national cultural history, as the 19th century proved crucial to the emancipation of Croatians and saw unprecedented developments in all fields of art and culture, giving rise to many historical figures.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The Ministry of Culture is tasked with preserving the nation's cultural and natural heritage and overseeing its development.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Further activities supporting the development of culture are undertaken at the local government level.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The UNESCO's World Heritage List includes ten sites in Croatia and a list of Intangible Cultural Heritage of Croatia.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The country is rich with intangible culture and holds 15 of UNESCO's World's intangible culture masterpieces, ranking fourth in the world.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] A global cultural contribution from Croatia is the necktie, derived from the cravat originally worn by the 17th-century Croatian mercenaries in France.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] In 2019, Croatia had 95 professional theatres, 30 professional children's theatres, and 51 amateur theatres visited by more than 2.27 million viewers per year.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Professional theatres employ 1,195 artists.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] There are 42 professional orchestras, ensembles, and choirs, attracting an annual attendance of 297 thousand.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] There are 75 cinemas with 166 screens and attendance of 5.026 million.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Croatia has 222 museums, visited by more than 2.71 million people in 2023.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Furthermore, there are 1,768 libraries, containing 26.8 million volumes, and 19 state archives.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The book publishing market is dominated by several major publishers and the industry's centrepiece event—Interliber exhibition held annually at Zagreb Fair.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Architecture in Croatia reflects influences of bordering nations.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Austrian and Hungarian influence is visible in public spaces and buildings in the north and the central regions, architecture found along coasts of Dalmatia and Istria exhibits Venetian influence.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Squares named after culture heroes, parks, and pedestrian-only zones, are features of Croatian towns and cities, especially where large scale Baroque urban planning took place, for instance in Osijek (Tvrđa), Varaždin, and Karlovac.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The subsequent influence of the Art Nouveau was reflected in contemporary architecture.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The architecture is the Mediterranean with a Venetian and Renaissance influence in major coastal urban areas exemplified in works of Giorgio da Sebenico and Nicolas of Florence such as the Cathedral of St.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The oldest preserved examples of Croatian architecture are the 9th-century churches, with the largest and the most representative among them being Church of St.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Besides the architecture encompassing the oldest artworks, there is a history of artists in Croatia reaching the Middle Ages.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] In that period the stone portal of the Trogir Cathedral was made by Radovan, representing the most important monument of Romanesque sculpture from Medieval Croatia.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The Renaissance had the greatest impact on the Adriatic Sea coast since the remainder was embroiled in the Hundred Years' Croatian–Ottoman War.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] With the waning of the Ottoman Empire, art flourished during the Baroque and Rococo.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The 19th and 20th centuries brought affirmation of numerous Croatian artisans, helped by several patrons of the arts such as bishop Josip Juraj Strossmayer.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Croatian artists of the period achieving renown were Vlaho Bukovac, Ivan Meštrović, and Ivan Generalić.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The Baška tablet, a stone inscribed with the glagolitic alphabet found on the Krk island and dated to c.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] 1100, is considered to be the oldest surviving prose in Croatian.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The beginning of more vigorous development of Croatian literature is marked by the Renaissance and Marko Marulić.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Croatian music varies from classical operas to modern-day rock.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Vatroslav Lisinski created the country's first opera, *Love and Malice*, in 1846.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Ivan Zajc composed more than a thousand pieces of music, including masses and oratorios.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Pianist Ivo Pogorelić has performed across the world.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] In Croatia, the Constitution guarantees the freedom of the press and the freedom of speech.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Croatia ranked 64th in the 2019 Press Freedom Index report compiled by Reporters Without Borders which noted that journalists who investigate corruption, organised crime or war crimes face challenges and that the Government was trying to influence the public broadcaster HRT's editorial policies.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] In its 2019 Freedom in the World report, the Freedom House classified freedoms of press and speech in Croatia as generally free from political interference and manipulation, noting that journalists still face threats and occasional attacks.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The state-owned news agency HINA runs a wire service in Croatian and English on politics, economics, society, and culture.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Also, there are 21 regional or local DVB-T television channels.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The HRT is also broadcasting a satellite TV channel.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] In 2020, there were 147 radio stations and 27 TV stations in Croatia.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Cable television and IPTV networks are gaining ground.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Cable television already serves 450 thousand people, around 10% of the total population of the country.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] In 2010, 267 newspapers and 2,676 magazines were published in Croatia.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The print media market is dominated by the Croatian-owned Hanza Media and Austrian-owned Styria Media Group who publish their flagship dailies *Jutarnji list*, *Večernji list* and *24sata*.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Other influential newspapers are *Novi list* and *Slobodna Dalmacija*.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] In 2020, *24sata* was the most widely circulated daily newspaper, followed by *Večernji list* and *Jutarnji list*.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Croatia competed in the Eurovision Song Contest as part of Yugoslavia since 1961.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The first and only victory Yugoslavia achieved in the competition was accomplished by the Croatian pop band Riva in 1989.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Since its debut at the 1993 contest, Croatia won two fourth places at the 1996 and 1999 contests, and one second place at the 2024 contest, marking the country's best result to date as an independent nation.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Croatia's film industry is small and heavily subsidised by the government, mainly through grants approved by the Ministry of Culture with films often being co-produced by HRT.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Croatian cinema produces between five and ten feature films per year.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Pula Film Festival, the national film awards event held annually in Pula, is the most prestigious film event featuring national and international productions.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Animafest Zagreb, founded in 1972, is the prestigious annual film festival dedicated to the animated film.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The first greatest accomplishment by Croatian filmmakers was achieved by Dušan Vukotić when he won the 1961 Academy Award for Best Animated Short Film for *Ersatz* (Croatian: *Surogat*).
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Croatian film producer Branko Lustig won the Academy Awards for Best Picture for *Schindler's List* and *Gladiator*.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Here We Go Again* on island of Vis, *Succession* on the island of Korčula, *Hercules*, *The Weekend Away*, *Bliss* in Split, *The Peacemaker*, *Lee* and many others.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Croatia became international filming location due to its biodiversity, landscape that can accommodate every visual requirements and cheaper filming costs.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] In last 11 years there has been 122 projects for international films in Croatia, and €263 million spent as part of the Filming in Croatia which increased in last years due to high demand for its location.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Croatian traditional cuisine varies from one region to another.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Dalmatia and Istria have culinary influences of Italian and other Mediterranean cuisines which prominently feature various seafood, cooked vegetables and pasta, and condiments such as olive oil and garlic.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Austrian, Hungarian, Turkish, and Balkan culinary styles influenced continental cuisine.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] In that area, meats, freshwater fish, and vegetable dishes are predominant.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] There are two distinct wine-producing regions in Croatia.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The continental in the northeast of the country, especially Slavonia, produces premium wines, particularly whites.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Along the north coast, Istrian and Krk wines are similar to those in neighbouring Italy, while further south in Dalmatia, Mediterranean-style red wines are the norm.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Annual production of wine exceeds 72 million litres as of 2017.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Croatia was almost exclusively a wine-consuming country up until the late 18th century when a more massive beer production and consumption started.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] There are 11 restaurants in Croatia with a Michelin star and 89 restaurants bearing some of the Michelin's marks.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Croatia has a long tradition of sports dating back to Roman times, followed by popular medieval knights' tournaments.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Modern organized sports began in the late 19th century with the founding of sports associations like Hrvatski Sokol in 1874.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] By the early 20th century, many sports organizations emerged, including the Croatian Sports Association established in 1909.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Croatian sports' development has been closely related to the Olympic movement, with Franjo Bučar playing a key role in promoting sports for Croatian independence.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Sport is part of the school curriculum, and many children engage in extracurricular activities.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] To support sports development, Croatia enacted the National Sport Programme in 2019.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Funding for sports comes from the state budget, sponsorship, and membership fees.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The Croatian Olympic Committee, established in 1991, oversees over 80 national sports associations.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The most popular sports in Croatia are football, basketball, handball, and water polo.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] In 2024, there were over 4,500 chess association members.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] With about 12,500 sports associations, football is the most popular sport, hosting nearly 1,500 clubs and 110,000 players, achieving significant milestones, including bronze at the 1998 World Cup, silver at the 2018 World Cup and another bronze at 2022 World Cup.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Croatians have participated in the Olympics since 1992 and have won 59 Olympic medals, including 20 gold.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The national tennis team has won two Davis Cup titles and won a gold medal at the 2020 Summer Olympics in men's doubles.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] The national handball and water polo teams are also been successful, each achieving multiple championships and medals.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] Rowing has seen success as well, winning multiple Olympic and World Championship medals.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/croatia-p02] In gymnastics, athletes have also made their mark, winning medals in European and World Championships.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Doha was founded in the 1820s as an offshoot of Al Bidda.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] It was officially declared as the country's capital in 1971, when Qatar gained independence from being a British protectorate.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] As the commercial capital of Qatar and one of the emergent financial centers in the Middle East, Doha is ranked "Beta+" on the Globalization and World Cities Research Network scale of "integration into the world city network".
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Metropolitan Doha includes parts of Al Rayyan such as Education City, an area devoted to research and education, and Hamad Medical City, an administrative area of medical care.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] It also includes Doha Sports City, or Aspire Zone, an international sports destination that includes Khalifa International Stadium, Hamad Aquatic Centre; and the Aspire Dome.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] The city was host to the first ministerial-level meeting of the Doha Development Round of World Trade Organization negotiations.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] It was also selected as host city of several sporting events, including the 2006 Asian Games, the 2011 Pan Arab Games, the 2019 World Beach Games, the World Aquatics Championships, the FIVB Volleyball Club World Championship, the WTA Finals and most of the games at the 2011 AFC Asian Cup.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] In December 2011, the World Petroleum Council held the 20th World Petroleum Conference in Doha.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Additionally, the city hosted the 2012 UNFCCC Climate Negotiations and the 2022 FIFA World Cup.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] The city will host the 2027 FIBA Basketball World Cup.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] The city also hosted the 140th Inter-Parliamentary Union Assembly in April 2019 and hosted the 18th yearly session of the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change in 2012.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] According to the Ministry of Municipality and Environment of Qatar, the name "Doha" originated from the Arabic term *dohat*, meaning "roundness"—a reference to the rounded bays surrounding the area's coastline.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] The city of Doha was formed seceding from another local settlement known as Al Bidda.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] The earliest documented mention of Al Bidda was made in 1681 by the Carmelite Convent, in an account that chronicles several settlements in Qatar.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] In the record, the ruler and a fort in the confines of Al Bidda are alluded to.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Carsten Niebuhr, a German explorer who visited the Arabian Peninsula, created one of the first maps to depict the settlement in 1765, in which he labelled it as 'Guttur'.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] David Seaton, a British political resident in Muscat, wrote the first English record of Al Bidda in 1801.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] He refers to the town as 'Bedih' and describes the geography and defensive structures in the area.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] He stated that the town had recently been settled by the Sudan tribe (singular Al-Suwaidi), whom he considered to be pirates.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Seaton attempted to bombard the town with his warship, but returned to Muscat upon finding that the waters were too shallow to position his warship within striking distance.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Colebrook, who visited Al Bidda, remarked on the recent depopulation of the town.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] The same year, an agreement known as the General Maritime Treaty was signed between the East India Company and the sheikhs of several Persian Gulf settlements (some of which were later known as the Trucial Coast).
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] It acknowledged British authority in the Persian Gulf and sought to end piracy and the slave trade.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Bahrain became a party to the treaty, and it was assumed that Qatar, perceived as a dependency of Bahrain by the British, was also a party to it.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Qatar, however, was not asked to fly the prescribed Trucial flag.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] As punishment for alleged piracy committed by the inhabitants of Al Bidda and breach of the treaty, an East India Company vessel bombarded the town in 1821.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] They razed the town, forcing between 300 and 400 natives to flee and temporarily take shelter on the islands between Qatar and the Trucial Coast.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Doha was founded in the vicinity of Al Bidda sometime during the 1820s.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] In January 1823, the British political resident John MacLeod visited Al Bidda to meet with the ruler and initial founder of Doha, Buhur bin Jubrun, who was also the chief of the Al-Buainain tribe.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] MacLeod noted that Al Bidda was the only substantial trading port in the peninsula during this time.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Following the founding of Doha, written records often conflated Al Bidda and Doha due to their extremely close proximity.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Later that year, Lieutenant Guy and Lieutenant Brucks mapped and wrote a description of the two settlements.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Despite being mapped as two separate entities, they were referred to under the collective name of Al Bidda in the written description.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] In 1828, Mohammed bin Khamis, a prominent member of the Al-Buainain tribe and successor of Buhur bin Jubrun as chief of Al Bidda, was embroiled in controversy.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] He had murdered a native of Bahrain, prompting the Al Khalifa sheikh to imprison him.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] In response, the Al-Buainain tribe revolted, provoking the Al Khalifa to destroy the tribe's fort and evict them to Fuwayrit and Ar Ru'ays.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] This incident allowed the Al Khalifa additional jurisdiction over the town.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] With essentially no effective ruler, Al Bidda and Doha became a sanctuary for pirates and outlaws.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] In November 1839, an outlaw from Abu Dhabi named Ghuleta took refuge in Al Bidda, evoking a harsh response from the British.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Nott, a British naval commander, demanded that Salemin bin Nasir Al-Suwaidi, chief of the Sudan tribe (Suwaidi) in Al Bidda, take Ghuleta into custody and warned him of consequences in the case of non-compliance.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Al-Suwaidi obliged the British request in February 1840 and also arrested the pirate Jasim bin Jabir and his associates.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Despite the compliance, the British demanded a fine of 300 German krones in compensation for the damages incurred by pirates off the coast of Al Bidda; namely for the piracy committed by bin Jabir.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] In February 1841, British naval squadrons arrived in Al Bidda and ordered Al-Suwaidi to meet the British demand, threatening consequences if he declined.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Al-Suwaidi ultimately declined on the basis that he was uninvolved in bin Jabir's actions.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] On 26 February, the British fired on Al Bidda, striking a fort and several houses.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Al-Suwaidi then paid the fine in full following threats of further action by the British.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Isa bin Tarif, a powerful tribal chief from the Al Bin Ali tribe, moved to Doha in May 1843.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] He subsequently evicted the ruling Sudan tribe and installed the Al-Maadeed and Al-Kuwari tribes in positions of power.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Bin Tarif died in the Battle of Fuwayrit against the ruling family of Bahrain in 1847.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] The Al Thani family migrated to Doha from Fuwayrit shortly after Bin Tarif's death in 1847 under the leadership of Mohammed bin Thani.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] In the proceeding years, the Al Thani family assumed control of the town.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] At various times, they swapped allegiances between the two prevailing powers in the area: the Al Khalifa of Bahrain and the Saudis.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] In 1867, many ships and troops were sent from Bahrain to assault the towns Al Wakrah and Doha over a series of disputes.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Abu Dhabi joined on Bahrain's behalf due to the perception that Al Wakrah served as a refuge for fugitives from Oman.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Later that year, the combined forces sacked the two Qatari towns with around 2,700 men in what came to be known as the Qatari–Bahraini War.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] A British record later stated that "the towns of Doha and Wakrah were, at the end of 1867 temporarily blotted out of existence, the houses being dismantled and the inhabitants deported".
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] The joint Bahraini-Abu Dhabi incursion and subsequent Qatari counterattack prompted the British political agent, Colonel Lewis Pelly, to impose a settlement in 1868.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Pelly's mission to Bahrain and Qatar and the peace treaty that resulted were milestones in Qatar's history.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] It implicitly recognized Qatar as a distinct entity independent from Bahrain and explicitly acknowledged the position of Mohammed bin Thani as the main representative of the peninsula's tribes.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] In December 1871, the Ottomans established a presence in the country with 100 of their troops occupying the Musallam fort in Doha.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] This was accepted by Mohammad bin Thani's son, Jassim Al Thani, who wished to protect Doha from Saudi incursions.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] The Ottoman commander, Major Ömer Bey, compiled a report on Al Bidda in January 1872, stating that it was an "administrative centre" with around 1,000 houses and 4,000 inhabitants.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Disagreement over tribute and interference in internal affairs arose, eventually leading to the Battle of Al Wajbah in March 1893.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Al Bidda Fort served as the final point of retreat for Ottoman troops.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] While they were garrisoned in the fort, their corvette fired indiscriminately at the townspeople, killing many civilians.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] The Ottomans eventually surrendered after Jassim Al Thani's troops cut off the town's water supply.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] An Ottoman report compiled the same year reported that Al Bidda and Doha had a combined population of 6,000 inhabitants, jointly referring to both towns by the name of 'Katar'.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Doha was classified as the eastern section of Katar.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] The Ottomans held a passive role in Qatar's politics from the 1890s onward until fully relinquishing control during the beginning of the First World War.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Pearling had come to play a pivotal commercial role in Doha by the 20th century.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] The population increased to around 12,000 inhabitants in the first half of the 20th century due to the flourishing pearl trade.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] A British political resident noted that should the supply of pearls drop, Qatar would 'practically cease to exist'.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] In 1907, the city accommodated 350 pearling boats with a combined crew size of 6,300 men.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] By this time, the average prices of pearls had more than doubled since 1877.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] The pearl market collapsed that year, forcing Jassim Al Thani to sell the country's pearl harvest at half its value.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] The aftermath of the collapse resulted in the establishment of the country's first custom house in Doha.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Lorimer authored an extensive handbook for British agents in the Persian Gulf entitled *Gazetteer of the Persian Gulf* in 1908.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Lorimer goes on to list and describe the districts of Doha, which at the time included the still-existing districts of Al Mirqab, As Salatah, Al Bidda and Rumeilah.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] As for Doha's population, Lorimer asserts that "the inhabitants of Dohah are estimated to amount, inclusive of the Turkish military garrison of 350 men, to about 12,000 souls".
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] He qualified this statement with a tabulated overview of the various tribes and ethnic groups living in the town.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] In April 1913, the Ottomans agreed to a British request to withdraw all their troops from Qatar.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Ottoman presence in the peninsula ceased, when in August 1915, the Ottoman fort in Al Bidda was evacuated shortly after the start of World War I.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] One year later, Qatar agreed to be a British protectorate with Doha as its official capital.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Buildings at the time were simple dwellings of one or two rooms, built from mud, stone, and coral.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Oil concessions in the 1920s and 1930s, and subsequent oil drilling in 1939, heralded the beginning of slow economic and social progress in the country.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] However, revenues were somewhat diminished due to the devaluation of pearl trade in the Persian Gulf brought on by the introduction of the cultured pearl and the Great Depression.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] The collapse of the pearl trade caused a significant population drop throughout the country.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] It was not until the 1950s and 1960s that the country saw significant monetary returns from oil drilling.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Qatar was not long in exploiting the new-found wealth from oil concessions, and slum areas were quickly razed to be replaced by more modern buildings.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] In 1950, British adviser to the Emir, Phillip L.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Plant, initiated several municipal projects.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Starting with remodeling the old complex of the Old Amiri Palace, Plant then initiated the construction of a seaside road about a half-mile in length which opened up and made accessible the half dozen jetties along Doha's most built-up section.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] The first formal boys' school was established in Doha in 1952, followed three years later by the establishment of a girls' school.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Historically, Doha had been a commercial port of local significance.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] However, the shallow water of the bay prevented bigger ships from entering the port until the 1970s, when its deep-water port was completed.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Further changes followed with extensive land reclamation, which led to the development of the crescent-shaped bay.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] From the 1950s to 1970s, the population of Doha grew from around 14,000 inhabitants to over 83,000, with foreign immigrants constituting about two-thirds of the overall population.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] In April 1970, the first Qatari constitution was ratified under an Interim Basic Statute.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] This demanded that there be a formation of the first council of ministers, as well as a cabinet.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] The following year, Sheikh Khalifa bin Hamad Al Thani, the heir apparent, and prime minister dissolved the 1916 treaty, officially declaring Qatar as an independent state.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] In 1973, the University of Qatar was opened by emiri decree, and in 1975, the Qatar National Museum opened in what was originally the ruler's palace.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] During the 1970s, all old neighborhoods in Doha were razed and the inhabitants moved to new suburban developments, such as Al Rayyan, Madinat Khalifa and Al Gharafa.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] The Doha Metropolitan Area's population grew from 89,000 in the 1970s to over 434,000 in 1997.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Additionally, land policies resulted in the total land area increasing to over 7,100 hectares (about 17,000 acres) by 1995, an increase from 130 hectares in the middle of the 20th century.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] In 1983, a hotel and conference center was developed at the north end of the Corniche.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] The 15-story Sheraton hotel structure in this center was the tallest structure in Doha until the 1990s.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] In 1993, the Qatar Open became the first major sports event to be hosted in the city.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Two years later, Qatar stepped in to host the FIFA World Youth Championship, with all the matches being played in Doha-based stadiums.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] The Al Jazeera Arabic news channel began broadcasting from Doha in 1996.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] In the late 1990s, the government planned the construction of Education City, a 2,500 hectare Doha-based complex mainly for educational institutes.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Since the start of the 21st century, Doha attained significant media attention due to the hosting of several global events and the inauguration of several architectural mega-projects.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] One of the largest projects launched by the government was The Pearl-Qatar, an artificial island off the coast of West Bay, which launched its first district in 2004.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] In 2006, Doha was selected to host the Asian Games, leading to the development of a 250-hectare sporting complex known as Aspire Zone.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] During this time, new cultural attractions were constructed in the city, with older ones being restored.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] In 2006, the government launched a restoration program to preserve Souq Waqif's architectural and historical identity.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Parts constructed after the 1950s were demolished whereas older structures were refurbished.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Katara Cultural Village was opened in the city in 2010 and has hosted the Doha Tribeca Film Festival since then.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] The main outcome of the World Trade Organization Ministerial Conference of 2013 was the Trade Facilitation Agreement.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] The agreement aims to make it easier and cheaper to import and export by improving customs procedures and making rules more transparent.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Reducing global trade costs by 1% would increase worldwide income by more than US$40 billion, 65% of which would go to developing countries.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] The gains from the Trade Facilitation Agreement are expected to be distributed among all countries and regions, with developing landlocked countries benefiting the most.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] The Trade Facilitation Agreement will enter into force upon its ratification by 2/3 of WTO Members.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] The EU ratified the agreement in October 2015.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] In Bali, WTO members also agreed on a series of Doha agriculture and development issues.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Now modernizing the city while preserving traditions is part of the country's long-term plan, Qatar National Vision 2030.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] On 9 September 2025, Israel carried out an airstrike in Doha, targeting a residential complex in the West Bay Lagoon district which housed senior Hamas negotiators in Doha, who were working on a ceasefire agreement with Israel to end the Gaza war.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] It was the first time that Israel launched a direct attack on one of the Gulf Cooperation Council members.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Doha is located on the central-east portion of Qatar, bordered by the Persian Gulf on its coast.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Land reclamation off the coast has added 400 hectares of land and 30 km (19 mi) of coastline.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Half of the 22 km2 (8.5 sq mi) of surface area which Hamad International Airport was constructed on was reclaimed land.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] The geology of Doha is primarily composed of weathered unconformity on the top of the Eocene period Dammam Formation, forming dolomitic limestone.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Street cats, having first been introduced in the 1960s to deal with the country's rodent infestations, are now widespread in Doha, with government estimates putting the total population at between 2 million and 3 million.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] The Gulf sand gecko, having been first observed in Qatar on Doha's islands in 2013, is now also found on the promontory in coastal and saline places.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Flowers of the sacred datura (*Datura innoxia*), crown daisy (*Glebionis coronaria*), wild chamomile (*Matricaria chamomilla*), and glandular speedwell (*Veronica cymbalaria*) have also been observed in rare instances, the latter as a weed.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Herbs such as *rabl* (*Plantago psyllium*), which is found primarily near roadsides, and *shih* (*Artemisia inculta*) also occur infrequently.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] The Pearl is an artificial island in Doha with a surface area of nearly 400 ha (1,000 acres) The total project has been estimated to cost $15 billion upon completion.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Other islands off Doha's coast include Palm Tree Island, Shrao's Island, Al Safliya Island, and Al Aaliya Island.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] In a 2010 survey of Doha's coastal waters conducted by the Qatar Statistics Authority, it was found that its maximum depth was 7.5 meters (25 ft) and minimum depth was 2 meters (6 ft 7 in).
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] The waters had an average pH of 7.83, a salinity of 49.0 psu, an average temperature of 22.7 °C (72.9 °F) and 5.5 mg/L of dissolved oxygen.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Doha has a hot desert climate (Köppen climate classification *BWh*) with long, extremely hot summers and short, mild to warm winters.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] The average high temperatures between May and September surpass 38 °C (100 °F) and often approach 45 °C (113 °F).
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Humidity is usually the lowest in May and June.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Dewpoints can surpass 30 °C (86 °F) in the summer.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Throughout the summer, the city averages almost no precipitation, and less than 20 mm (0.79 in) during other months.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Rainfall is scarce, at a total of 75 mm (2.95 in) per year, falling on isolated days mostly between October and March.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] The winter's days are relativity warm while the sun is up and cool during the night.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] The temperature rarely drops below 7 °C (45 °F).
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] The highest temperature recorded was 50.4 °C (122.7 °F) on 14 July 2010, which is the highest temperature ever recorded in Qatar.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] A significant portion of Qatar's population lives within Doha and its metropolitan area.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] The district with the highest population density is the central area of Al Najada, which also accommodates the highest total population in the country.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] The population density across the greater Doha region ranges from 20,000 people per km2 to 25–50 people per km2.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Doha saw explosive growth rates in population in the first decade of the 21st century, absorbing the majority of the thousands of people then immigrating to Qatar every month.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Doha's population is around one million, with the population of the city more than doubling from 2000 to 2010.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] The population of Doha is overwhelmingly composed of expatriates, with Qatari nationals forming a minority.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] The largest portion of expatriates in Qatar are from South-East and South Asian countries, mainly India, Pakistan, Sri Lanka, Nepal, the Philippines, and Bangladesh with large numbers of expatriates also coming from the Levant Arab countries, Djibouti, Somalia, North Africa, and East Asia.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Doha is also home to many expatriates from Europe, North America, South Africa and Australia.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Arabic is the official language of Qatar.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] English is commonly used as a second language, and a rising lingua franca, especially in commerce.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] As there is a large expatriate population in Doha, languages such as Malayalam, Tamil, Bengali, Tagalog, Spanish, Sinhala, French, Urdu and Hindi are widely spoken.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] In 2004, the Foreign Ownership of Real Estate Law was passed, permitting non-Qatari citizens to buy land in designated areas of Doha, including the West Bay Lagoon, the Qatar Pearl, and the new Lusail City.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Prior to this, expatriates were prohibited from owning land in Qatar.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Ownership by foreigners in Qatar entitles them to a renewable residency permit, which allows them to live and work in Qatar.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] The majority of residents in Doha are Muslim.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] A majority of mosques are either Salafi or Sunni-oriented.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Catholics account for over 90% of the 150,000 Christian population in Doha.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Following decrees by the Emir for the allocation of land to churches, the first Catholic church, Our Lady of the Rosary, was opened in Doha in March 2008.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] The church structure is discreet and Christian symbols are not displayed on the outside of the building.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Several other churches exist in Doha, including the St.Isaac and St.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] George Greek Orthodox Church of Qatar, Doha, Qatar St.Isaac and St.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] George Greek Orthodox Church of Qatar the Syro-Malabar Church, Malankara Orthodox Church, Mar Thoma Church (affiliated with the Anglicans, but not part of the Communion), CSI Church, Syro-Malankara Church and a Pentecostal church.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] At the turn of the 20th century, Doha was divided into 9 main districts.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] In the 2010 census, there were more than 60 districts recorded in Doha Municipality.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Some districts, such as As Salatah al Jadidah and Fereej Bin Mahmoud, essentially function as neighborhoods designated for particular tribes, as these tribes were the earliest to settle the area and were majority landholders.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Shortly after Qatar gained independence, many of the districts of old Doha including Al Najada, Al Asmakh and Old Al Hitmi faced gradual decline and as a result, much of their historical architecture has been demolished.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Instead, the government shifted their focus toward the Doha Bay area, which housed vital business districts such as Al Dafna and West Bay.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] The city is the headquarters of numerous domestic and international organizations, including the country's largest oil and gas companies, QatarEnergy and QatarEnergy LNG.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Doha's economy is built primarily on the revenue the country has made from its oil and natural gas industries.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Doha was included in Fortune's 15 best new cities for business in 2011.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Beginning in the late 20th century, the government launched numerous initiatives to diversify the country's economy to decrease its dependence on oil and gas resources.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Doha International Airport was constructed in a bid to solidify the city's diversification into the tourism industry.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] This was replaced by Hamad International Airport in 2014.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] The new airport is almost twice the size of the former and features two of the longest runways in the world.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Thirty-nine new hotels were under construction in the city in 2011.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] As a result of Doha's rapid population boom and increased housing demands, real estate prices rose significantly through 2014.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Real estate prices experienced a further spike after Qatar won the rights to host the 2022 FIFA World Cup.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Al Asmakh, a Qatari real estate firm, released a report in 2014 which revealed substantial increases in real estate prices following a peak in 2008.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Prices increased 5 to 10% in the first quarter of 2014 from the end of 2013.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] A 2015 study conducted by Numbeo, a crowd-sourced database, named Doha as the 10th most expensive city to live in globally.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] This rate of growth led to the development of planned communities in and around the city.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Although the fall in oil prices since 2014 and a diplomatic crisis with Qatar's neighbors slowed growth in the city's population, government spending was increased to maintain the growth in real estate in metropolitan Doha.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Expatriate workers remitted $60bn between 2006 and 2012, with 54 percent of the workers' remittances of $60bn routed to Asian countries, followed by Arab nations that accounted for nearly half that volume (28 percent).
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] India was the top destination of the remittances, followed by the Philippines, while the US, Egypt and the neighbouring UAE followed.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Remittances in 2014 totaled $11.2 billion, amounting to 5.3% of Qatar's GDP.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Doha is considered as the most important tourist city in Qatar.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Qatar's tourism sector is also a key focus of its economic diversification strategy.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] The country is investing in the development of new tourism infrastructure, such as hotels and resorts, and promoting its cultural attractions, such as the Museum of Islamic Art and the Katara Cultural Village to attract visitors from around the world.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] In addition, Qatar Airways has become one of the world's leading airlines, connecting the country to major cities across the globe.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Qatar has also been attracting major international events to the country, such as the FIFA World Cup 2022, which attracted over about 1 million visitors over the course of the tournament.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] The tournament itself ultimately made up 0.7–1.0 percent of Qatar's 2022 GDP, with World Cup-related tourism and broadcasting revenue estimated at US$2.3–4.1 billion.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] High and rising incomes in Qatar offer significant opportunities in culinary establishments and retail sectors.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Premium and healthy brands are especially well received.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Convenience food is also an increasingly important sector for younger Qataris and visitors.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] In recent years, Qatar has been taking steps to diversify its economy and reduce its reliance on oil and gas revenues.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] The country has launched several initiatives aimed at promoting non-oil sectors such as tourism, finance, and technology.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] For example, Qatar has invested heavily in building world-class infrastructure, including the Hamad International Airport and the Qatar Free Zones Authority, to attract foreign investors and businesses to set up shop in the country.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Moreover, Qatar has also been working towards creating a more business-friendly environment by streamlining regulations and offering incentives to start-ups and small businesses.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] The country's ambition in this area can already be seen in developments like the recently completed M7 building in downtown Doha.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] This futuristic five-story construction is described as an epicentre for innovation and entrepreneurship in design, fashion, and technology.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] The latest research by the World Travel and Tourism Council (WTTC) which highlighted the top 10 cities where international travelers spent the most money in 2022, showed Doha at the number 2 spot with $16.8 billion.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Qatar has received over 2.56 million visitors from January until 25 August 2023, exceeding the full year arrival figures from 2022, representing a 157 per cent increase over the same period last year, according to a report by Zawya citing figures released yesterday by Qatar Tourism (QT).
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Doha named Arab tourism capital for 2023.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Non-GCC tourists made up 66% of all visitors in October, an increase of 10% from the previous month 2023.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Doha in 2023 hosted International Horticultural Expo 2023.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Spanning 1.7 million square meters, the event took place in Al Bidda Park, one of the biggest parks in Doha, which overlooks the Persian Gulf.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] In Doha's traditional architecture, the primary building material was locally quarried limestone, with walls typically measuring 0.4 metres (1 ft 4 in) to 0.6 metres (2 ft 0 in) thick, constructed using two rows of large facing stones with a core of mud, gravel, and smaller stones.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] These walls were then covered with clay-rich mud or gypsum-based render.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Plaster, known as *juss*, was made from crushed beachrock, shell, baked lime, or gypsum, and applied in three layers for both functional and decorative purposes.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Roofing was characteristically flat, utilizing mangrove beams (*danshal*) imported from East Africa, overlaid with split bamboo, woven reed, and palm mats, then sealed with tamped earth.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Distinctive architectural elements included colonnaded verandas (liwan) with lintels made of mangrove poles bound with jute rope, and wooden waterspouts for drainage.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Valuable materials such as wooden beams, windows, and doors were often recycled from older structures.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Many of the older structures (1960–1970s) in the Old Doha districts have been demolished to make space for new buildings.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] A number of schemes have been taken to preserve the city's cultural and architectural heritage, such as the Qatar Museums Authority's 'Al Turath al Hai' ('living heritage') initiative.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Katara Cultural Village is a model village in Doha launched by Sheikha Moza bint Nasser under Qatar Foundation to preserve the cultural identity of the country.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] During the mid-20th century, Qatar saw a transition from traditional building techniques to more modern ones.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] In the 1950s, a notable change was the adoption of concrete blocks with shell inclusions.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] These blocks were primarily produced locally and incorporated a distinctive shelly sand rich in small gastropod remains, a material abundant along Qatar's coastline.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] As Qatar progressed into the latter half of the 20th century, construction methods evolved, with the use of shell-infused concrete blocks gradually giving way to more standardized building materials.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] This newer phase of construction is characterized by the use of plain concrete blocks without shell content and reinforced concrete structures.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] New materials such as manufactured wood products including plywood and metal materials such as corrugated iron were also introduced.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] This period also saw the widespread adoption of air conditioning systems.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] In 2011, more than 50 towers were under construction in Doha, the largest of which was the Doha Convention Center Tower.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Constructions were suspended in 2012 following concerns that the tower would impede flight traffic and the site is being redeveloped into a park.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] In 2014, Abdullah Al Attiyah, a senior government official, announced that Qatar would spend $65bn on new infrastructure projects in upcoming years in preparation for the 2022 FIFA World Cup as well as progressing towards its objectives set out in the Qatar National Vision 2030.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Msheireb Downtown Doha, a 31-hectare development costing an estimated $5bn, was dubbed the largest inner city redevelopment of its kind when launched.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Comprising several quarters opened over different phases, Msheireb aims to preserve the historic downtown area.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] The new National Museum of Qatar (NMoQ) opened to the public on 28 March 2019.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] The museum features an innovative design by Pritzker Prize-winning architect Jean Nouvel that is inspired by the desert rose and grows organically around the original 20th century palace of Sheikh Abdullah Bin Jassim Al Thani.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] This important monument to Qatar's past is now preserved as the heart of the new NMoQ.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Doha Tower also known as *Burj Doha*, and previously named *Burj Qatar* and *Doha High Rise Office Building*, is a high rise tower in West Bay, Doha.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] On 18 October 2012, the building received the CTBUH Skyscraper Award for the Best Tall Building Worldwide from the CTBUH.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] The $125-million office building, designed by French architect Jean Nouvel, has a height of 238 metres (781 ft), with 46 stories.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Aspire Tower, also known as *The Torch Doha*, is a 300-metre-tall (980 ft) skyscraper hotel located in the Aspire Zone complex in Doha.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Designed by architect Hadi Simaan and AREP and engineer Ove Arup and Partners, the tower served as the focal point for the 15th Asian Games hosted by Qatar in December 2006.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] The tower is currently the tallest structure and building in Doha and Qatar.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] The Tornado Tower also called the *QIPCO Tower*, is a high-rise office skyscraper in Doha.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] The building stands at a height of 640 feet (195 m) tall with 52 floors.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Construction began in 2006 and was completed in 2008.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Museum of Islamic Art, *MIA* is a museum on one end of the seven-kilometer-long (4.3 mi) Corniche in Doha.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Pei's specifications, the museum is built on an island off an artificial projecting peninsula near the traditional *dhow* harbor.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] A purpose-built park surrounds the edifice on the eastern and southern facades while two bridges connect the southern front facade of the property with the main peninsula that holds the park.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] The western and northern facades are marked by the harbor showcasing the Qatari seafaring past.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] In September 2017, Qatar Museums appointed Julia Gonnella as new director of MIA.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Qatar National Library (QNL) is a modern facility which provides the people of Qatar with access to over one million books.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] The library is a non-profit organization operated under the umbrella of the Qatar Foundation.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] The plans for the new national library were announced by Sheikha Moza bint Nasser, chairperson of Qatar Foundation, on 19 November 2012, during a ceremony celebrating the 50th anniversary of the Dar Al Kutub Library in Doha.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Al-Thumama Stadium is a football stadium in Al Thumama district in Doha, located approximately 13 km (8.1 mi) south of the city center.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] It hosted the 2022 FIFA World Cup held in the country.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Msheireb Museums is a complex of history museums housed in four historic heritage houses of Msheireb Downtown Doha, the old commercial centre of the city.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Each house explores a different aspect of the country's history through the trades and careers of its former residents: slavery, the oil industry, and folk arts and traditions.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] The restoration of the four heritage houses Bin Jelmood House, Company House, Mohammed Bin Jassim House, and Radwani House into world-class museums is a part of the first phase of the Heritage Quarter of Msheireb Properties’ QR20 billion (US$5.5 billion), 310,000 sq m development.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] The museum was also included in the 2018 world's best new buildings list of the Royal Institute of British Architects.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] In the pre-modern era, Doha's architectural landscape was characterized by densely clustered dwellings interconnected by narrow passageways, a design that offered mutual shade, privacy, and safety to residents.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] This urban configuration persisted until the latter part of the 20th century.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Traditional building techniques in Doha emphasized climate adaptation.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Thick stone walls, often reaching 0.6 metres (2 ft 0 in) in width, served as effective thermal insulators, mitigating heat transfer to the interior.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Facades typically featured minimal fenestration to maintain privacy and regulate internal temperatures.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] When present, windows were often internal and shuttered, frequently shielded by expansive verandas to minimize solar heat gain.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] The *badgheer* system was used to facilitate air circulation for cooling.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] This encompassed both windcatchers and wall vents, with the latter being more prevalent in Doha.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Large open courtyards were integral to promoting air movement within structures.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Design elements such as horizontal apertures at wall bases and within roof screens generated cooling breezes and air circulation.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Ornate, perforated gypsum panels served dual purposes, acting as decorative elements while enhancing airflow within domiciles.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Due to excessive heat from the sun during the summer, some Doha-based building companies implemented various forms of cooling technology to alleviate the extremely torrid climatic conditions in the late 20th century.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] This included creating optical phenomena such as shadows, as well as more expensive techniques like ventilation, coolants, refrigerants, cryogenics, and dehumidifiers.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Discussions regarding temperature control have also been features of various scheduled events involving large crowds.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Other initiatives attempt to counter the heat by altering working hours, weather alteration methods such as cloud seeding, and using whiter and brighter construction materials to increase the albedo effects.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Nonetheless, despite these measures, Doha and other areas of Qatar could become uninhabitable for humans due to climate change by the end of the 21st century.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] One of the largest urban development projects in Qatar is Lusail City, a planned community north of Doha constructed at a cost of approximately $45bn and designed to accommodate 450,000 people.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Al Waab City, another planned community under development, is estimated to cost QR15 bn.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] In addition to housing 8,000 individuals, it will also have shopping malls, educational, and medical facilities.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p01] Gewan Island is the latest development of UDC comprising a 400,000 square metres (4,300,000 sq ft) mixed use development.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] To support the expanding city and increasing numbers of residents and commuters, Qatar has heavily invested in upgrading the infrastructure of Doha and Qatar.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] Since 2004, Doha has been undergoing a huge expansion to its transportation network, including the addition of new highways, a new airport in 2014, a new seaport in 2016, and an 85 kilometres (53 mi) metro system which went operational in 2019.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] One of the latest projects, expected to be delivered in 2024 is the Sharq Crossing in Doha Bay.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] At a cost of approximately $12 billion, the crossing is expected to connect Hamad International Airport with both Katara Cultural Village and West Bay.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] Three of the Doha Metro's four lines are currently fully operational.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] The system consists of the Red Line, the Gold Line, the Green Line, and the incomplete Blue Line.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] The Blue Line is expected to be completed in the second phase in 2025.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] Msheireb Station is the transfer station for all of the metro lines.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] The *Red Line* (also known as Coast Line) extends through Doha, running from Al Khor to Al Wakrah and Hamad Airport via the Red Line North and Red Line South.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] Doha Metro's *Green Line,* or Education Line, connects Doha to Education City and Al Riffa.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] Starting in Old Airport, the *Gold Line* (also known as Historic Line) will end in Al Rayyan and cover a distance of 30.6 kilometres (19.0 mi).
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] Lastly, the *Blue Line*, or City Line, will only cover the inner city of Doha, and is planned to be semi-circular with a length of 17.5 kilometres (10.9 mi).
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] Doha is served by Hamad International Airport which is Qatar's principal international gateway.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] The airport opened in 2014, replacing Doha International Airport.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] The airport is named after the previous Emir of Qatar, Hamad bin Khalifa Al Thani.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] Hamad International Airport became the first Middle Eastern airport to be awarded the Skytrax's World Best Airport for 2021 in the 2021 World Airport Awards, ending the 7-year dominance of Singapore's Changi Airport.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] Qatar's Hamad International Airport has been named the World's Best Airport for the second year running.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] The announcement took place at the Skytrax 2022 World Airport Awards, held at Passenger Terminal EXPO in Paris, France.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] There are a variety of taxi operators in the Doha area.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] A plurality of taxis across the city and Hamad International Airport are marked by a distinctive turquoise colour; these taxis are owned and operated by Mowasalat, a government-owned enterprise, under the brand name Karwa.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] Ride-hailing applications like Uber, Ryde, Badrgo, and Aabir are also readily available across the city.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] Doha is the educational center of the country and contains the highest preponderance of schools and colleges.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] In 1952, the first formal boys' school was opened in Doha.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] This was proceeded by the opening of the first formal girls' school three years later.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] The first university in the state, Qatar University, was opened in 1973.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] It provided separate faculties for men and women.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] Education City, a 14 km2 (5.4 sq mi) education complex launched by non-profit organization Qatar Foundation, began construction in 2000.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] It houses eight universities, the country's top high school, and offices for Al Jazeera's children television channel.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] It is geographically located in Al Rayyan municipality's Al Luqta, Al Gharrafa, Gharrafat Al Rayyan and Al Shagub districts, but falls under the umbrella of Metropolitan Doha.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] In 2009, the government launched the World Innovation Summit for Education (WISE), a global forum that brings together education stakeholders, opinion leaders and decision-makers from all over the world to discuss educational issues.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] The first edition was held in Doha in November 2009.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] Football is the most popular sport in Doha.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] There are six Doha-based sports clubs with football teams competing in the Qatar Stars League, the country's top football league.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] They are Al Ahli, Al Arabi, Al Sadd, Al-Duhail and Qatar SC.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] Al Sadd, Al Arabi and Qatar SC are the three most successful teams in the league's history.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] Numerous football tournaments have been hosted in Doha.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] The most prestigious tournaments include the 1988 and 2011 editions of the AFC Asian Cup and the 1995 FIFA World Youth Championship.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] In December 2010, Qatar won the right to host the 2022 FIFA World Cup.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] Three of the nine newly announced stadiums were constructed in Doha, including Sports City Stadium, Doha Port Stadium, and Qatar University Stadium.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] Additionally, the Khalifa International Stadium underwent expansion.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] Considering the country's rapid development for the 2022 World Cup, FIFA awarded the hosting rights of 2019 FIFA Club World Cup and 2020 FIFA Club World Cup also to Qatar.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] Doha was the host of the official 2005 FIBA Asia Championship, where Qatar's national basketball team finished 3rd, its best performance to date, and subsequently qualified for the Basketball World Cup.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] The city will host matches for the 2027 FIBA Basketball World Cup.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] The majority of the teams that make up the official Qatari Basketball League are based in Doha.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] Doha four times was the host of the official FIVB Volleyball Men's Club World Championship and three times host FIVB Volleyball Women's Club World Championship.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] Doha also hosted the Asian Volleyball Championship.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] In 2001, Qatar became the first country in the Middle East to hold a women's tennis tournament with the inauguration of its Qatar Ladies Open tournament.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] Doha also hosts International Tennis Federation (ITF) ladies tournaments.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] Doha hosted the 15th Asian Games, held in December 2006, spending a total of $2.8 billion for its preparation.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] The city also hosted the 3rd West Asian Games in December 2005.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] Doha was expected to host the 2011 Asian Indoor Games; but the Qatar Olympic Committee cancelled the event.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] The city submitted a bid for the 2016 Olympics.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] On 4 June 2008, the city was eliminated from the shortlist for the 2016 Olympic Games.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] On 26 August 2011, it was confirmed that Doha would bid for the 2020 Summer Olympics.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] Doha however failed to become a Candidate City for the 2020 Games.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] The MotoGP motorcycling grand prix of Doha is held annually at Losail International Circuit, located just outside the city boundaries.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] The city is also the location of the Grand Prix of Qatar for the F1 Powerboat World Championship, annually hosting a round in Doha Bay.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] Beginning in November 2009, Doha has been host of The Oryx Cup World Championship, a hydroplane boat race in the H1 Unlimited season.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] In April 2012 Doha was awarded both the 2014 FINA World Swimming Championships and the 2012 World Squash Championships.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] The fourth World Mindsports Championships took place in Doha from 19 – 27 August 2017, with the participation of more than 1,000 competitors.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] In 2014, Qatar was selected as the host of the 2019 World Athletics Championships, which is the seventeenth edition of the IAAF World Athletics Championships.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] Doha won the bid to host the event over Barcelona and Eugene.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] In 2020, Doha hosted the Qatar ExxonMobil Open, which received the Tournament of the Year award in the 250 category from the 2019 ATP Awards.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] The tournament won the award for the third time in five years.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] Aspire Academy was launched in 2004 with the aim of creating world-class athletes.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] It is situated in the Doha Sports City Complex, which also accommodates the Khalifa International Stadium, the Hamad Aquatic Centre, the Aspire Tower, and the Aspire Dome.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] The latter has hosted more than 50 sporting events since its inception, including some events during the 2006 Asian Games.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] Aspire Academy, a sporting academy for youth, is located in the center of Aspire Zone.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] Doha was chosen as the Arab Capital of Culture in 2010.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] Cultural weeks organized by the Ministry of Culture, which featured both Arab and non-Arab cultures, were held in Doha from April to June to celebrate the city's selection.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] The Museum of Islamic Art or MIA in Doha, opened in 2008, is regarded as one of the best museums in the region.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] This, and several other Qatari museums located in the city, like the Arab Museum of Modern Art, falls under the Qatar Museums Authority (QMA) which is led by Sheikha Al-Mayassa bint Hamad bin Khalifa Al-Thani, the sister of the emir of Qatar.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] The National Museum of Qatar, which was constructed in place of the original Qatar National Museum, opened to the public on 28 March 2019.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] The Doha Film Institute (DFI) is an organisation established in 2010 to oversee film initiatives and create a sustainable film industry in Qatar.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] Sheikha Al Mayassa bint Hamad bin Khalifa Al-Thani.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] The Doha Tribeca Film Festival (DTFF), partnered with the American-based Tribeca Film Festival, was held annually in Doha from 2009 to 2012.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] It emanated from a collaboration between the Doha Film Institute and Tribeca Enterprises.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] Celebrities such as Robert De Niro, Salma Hayek, Adel Emam, Mira Nair, and Kevin Spacey attended the festivals.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] The festivals and premieres took place in the Katara Cultural Village annually, as well as the Museum of Islamic Art in 2012.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] The DTFF premiered up to 87 films from all around the world.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] The major cinema operators in Doha are Vox, NOVO and Flik.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] Qatar's first radio station, Mosque Radio, began broadcasting in the 1960s from Doha.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] The multinational media conglomerate Al Jazeera Media Network is based in Doha with its wide variety of channels of which Al Jazeera Arabic, Al Jazeera English, Al Jazeera Documentary Channel, Al Jazeera Mubasher, beIN Sports Arabia and other operations are based in the TV Roundabout in the city.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] Al-Kass Sports Channel's headquarters is also located in Doha.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] Al Jazeera Media Network serves as the overarching entity overseeing Al Jazeera English, Al Jazeera Arabic, AJ+ along with several other fact-based media endeavors that bear the same distinct brand.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] Originally conceived as a satellite TV channel delivering Arabic news and current affairs, it now encompasses various platforms such as online, specialized television channels in numerous languages, and more.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] The organization is a private foundation for public benefit under Qatari law.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] There have been allegations of government control.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] It was founded in 1996 by the then Emir of Qatar Sheikh Hamad bin Khalifa Al Thani.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] The first official theatre troupe in the country was created in 1972 as the "Qatari Theatrical Troupe".
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] It went on to produce its first play the same year.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] The next year, a second troupe was founded as the Al Sadd Theatrical Troupe.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] By 1986, the first company had been founded with the intent of aiding troupes and actors in producing plays.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] Two further troupes were also created during this period: the Lights Theatrical Troupe and Folk Theatrical Troupe.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] In 1994, the four troupes were amalgamated into two troupes which were named the Qatari Theatrical Troupe and the Doha Theatrical Troupe.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] Theatre was introduced to Qatar in the mid-20th century.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/doha-p02] Theatrical performances are held at Qatar National Theater and at the Qatar National Convention Center in Doha.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] The history of the city probably dates back to the 7th century, when the town known as *Ragusa* was founded by refugees from Epidaurum (*Ragusa Vecchia*).
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] It was under protectorate of the Byzantine Empire and later under the sovereignty of the Republic of Venice.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] Between the 14th and 19th centuries, Dubrovnik ruled itself as a free state.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] The prosperity of the city was historically based on maritime trade; as the capital of the maritime Republic of Ragusa, it achieved a high level of development, particularly during the 15th and 16th centuries, as it became notable for its wealth and skilled diplomacy.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] At the same time, Dubrovnik became a cradle of Croatian literature.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] In his letter to Nikola Nalješković (1564), poet Ivan Vidalić named it "crown of Croatian cities".
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] The entire city was almost destroyed in a devastating earthquake in 1667.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] During the Napoleonic Wars, Dubrovnik was occupied by the French Empire forces, and then the Republic of Ragusa was abolished and incorporated into the Napoleonic Kingdom of Italy and later into the Illyrian Provinces of France.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] From the early 19th to early 20th centuries, Dubrovnik was part of the Kingdom of Dalmatia within the Austrian Empire.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] Dubrovnik became part of the Kingdom of Yugoslavia immediately upon its creation, and it was incorporated into its Zeta Banovina in 1929, before becoming part of the Banovina of Croatia upon its creation in 1939.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] During World War II, it was part of the Independent State of Croatia, an Axis puppet state, before being reincorporated into the Socialist Republic of Croatia in the Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] In 1991, during the Croatian War of Independence, Dubrovnik was besieged by the Yugoslav People's Army for seven months and suffered significant damage from shelling.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] After undergoing repair and restoration works in the 1990s and early 2000s, it re-emerged as one of the Mediterranean's top tourist destinations, as well as a popular filming location.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] Often called "*The Queen of the Adriatic"* Dubrovnik is considered one of the most popular destinations in the Adriatic and in Europe.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] The names *Dubrovnik* and *Ragusa* co-existed for several centuries.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] The name *Dubrovnik* of the Adriatic city is first recorded in the Charter of Ban Kulin (1189).
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] The most common explanation for the origin is from a Proto-Slavic word *dǫbъ meaning 'oak', and the term *dubrovnik* referring to 'oak wood' or 'oak forest', as *dǫbrava* means 'oakwood', 'forest'.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] The historical name *Ragusa* is recorded in the Greek form Ῥαούσιν (*Rhaousin*, Latinized *Ragusium*) in the 10th century.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] It was recorded in various forms in the medieval period, *Rausia*, *Lavusa*, *Labusa*, *Raugia*, *Rachusa*.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] Various attempts have been made to etymologize the name.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] Suggestions include derivation from Greek ῥάξ, ῥαγός "grape"; from Greek ῥώξ, ῥωγός "narrow passage"; Greek ῥωγάς "ragged (of rocks)", ῥαγή (ῥαγάς) "fissure"; from the name of the Epirote tribe of the *Rhogoi*, from an unidentified Illyrian substrate.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] A connection to the name of Sicilian Ragusa has also been proposed.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] Orel that the Proto-Albanian **rāguša* of Albanian *rrush* 'grape' is related to *Ragusa* or the source of the name.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] Putanec (1993) gives a review of etymological suggestion, and favours an explanation of the name as pre-Greek ("Pelasgian"), from a root cognate to Greek ῥαγή "fissure", with a suffix *-ussa* also found in the Greek name of Brač, *Elaphousa*.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] The name of the city in the native Dalmatian language, now extinct, was *Ragusa*, as shown by a 1325 letter in Dalmatian.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] The classical explanation of the name is due to Constantine VII's *De Administrando Imperio* (10th century).
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] According to this account, Ragusa (Ῥαούσιν) is the foundation of the refugees from Epidaurum (Ragusa Vecchia), a Greek city situated some 15 km (9 mi) to the south of Ragusa, when that city was destroyed in the Slavic incursions of the 7th century.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] The name is explained as a corruption of a Dalmatae/Romance word *Lausa*, the name of the rocky island on which the city was built (connected by Constantine to Greek λᾶας "rock, stone").
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] Dubrovnik was inhabited by the Illyrian tribe of Pleraei in ancient times.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] According to Constantine Porphyrogenitus's *De Administrando Imperio* (c.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] 950), Ragusa was founded in the 7th century, named after a "rocky island" called *Lausa*, by refugees from Epidaurum (Ragusa Vecchia), a Roman city situated some 15 km (9.3 mi) to the south, when that city was destroyed by Slavs fighting with the Avars.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] It was one of the Dalmatian city-states.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] Excavations in 2007 revealed a Byzantine basilica from the 8th century and parts of the city walls.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] The size of the old basilica clearly indicates that there was quite a large settlement at the time.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] There is also evidence for the presence of a settlement in the pre-Christian era, most notably the finding of ancient coins from the 3rd and 2nd century BC, as well as archeological fragments from the 1st century BC in the area of the old City port.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] After the fall of the Ostrogothic Kingdom, the town came under the protection of the Byzantine Empire.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] In the 12th and 13th centuries, Dubrovnik grew into an oligarchic republic.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] After the Crusades, Dubrovnik came under the sovereignty of Venice (1205–1358), which would give its institutions to the Dalmatian city.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] In 1240 Ragusa purchased the island of Lastovo from Stefan Uroš I, king of Serbia, who had rights over the island as ruler of parts of Zachlumia.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] After a fire destroyed most of the city on the night of August 16, 1296, a new urban plan was developed.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] By the Peace Treaty of Zadar in 1358, Dubrovnik achieved relative independence as a vassal-state of the Kingdom of Hungary.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] Between the 14th century and 1808, Dubrovnik ruled itself as a free state, although it was a tributary from 1382 to 1804 of the Ottoman Empire and paid an annual tribute to its sultan.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] The Republic reached its peak in the 15th and 16th centuries, when its thalassocracy rivalled that of the Republic of Venice and other Italian maritime republics.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] There are also signs of a long established Albanian population in the Ragusan hinterlands since at least the Medieval period.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] And a Ragusan document dating to 1285 states: "I heard a voice crying in the mountains in Albanian" (Audivi unam vocem clamantem in monte in lingua albanesca).
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] For centuries, Dubrovnik was an ally of Ancona, the other Adriatic maritime republic rival of Venice, which was itself the Ottoman Empire's chief rival for control of the Adriatic.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] This alliance enabled the two towns set on opposite sides of the Adriatic to resist attempts by the Venetians to make the Adriatic a "Venetian Bay", also controlling directly or indirectly all the Adriatic ports.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] Ancona and Dubrovnik developed an alternative trade route to the Venetian (Venice–Austria–Germany): starting in Dubrovnik it went on to Ancona, through Florence and ended in Flanders.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] Ragusa was an important base for the traffic of the Balkan slave trade, from which slaves were transported from the Balkans across the Adriatic Sea to the Aegean Sea, from which they were sold on to either Spain in the West or Egypt in the South.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] The Republic of Ragusa received its own Statutes as early as 1272, which, among other things, codified Roman practice and local customs.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] The Statutes included prescriptions for town planning and the regulation of quarantine (for sanitary reasons).
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] The Republic was an early adopter of what are now regarded as modern laws and institutions: a medical service was introduced in 1301, with the first pharmacy, still operating to this day, being opened in 1317.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] An almshouse was opened in 1347, and the first quarantine hospital (Lazarete) was established in 1377.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] Slave trading was abolished in 1418, and an orphanage opened in 1432.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] A 20 km (12 mi) water supply system, instead of a cistern, was constructed in 1438 by the Neapolitan architect and engineer Onofrio della Cava.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] He completed the aqueduct with two public fountains.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] He also built a number of mills along one of its branches.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] The city was ruled by the local aristocracy which was of Latin-Dalmatian extraction and formed two city councils.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] As usual for the time, they maintained a strict system of social classes.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] The republic abolished the slave trade early in the 15th century and valued liberty highly.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] The city successfully balanced its sovereignty between the interests of Venice and the Ottoman Empire for centuries.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] Latin was originally used in official documents of the Republic.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] Italian came to use in the early 15th century.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] A variant of the Dalmatian language was among the spoken ones, and was influenced by Croatian and Italian.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] The presence of Croatian in everyday speech increased in the late 13th century, and in literary works in the mid-15th century.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] In the coming decades, Dubrovnik became a cradle of Croatian literature.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] The economic wealth of the Republic was partially the result of the land it developed, but especially of seafaring trade.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] With the help of skilled diplomacy, Dubrovnik merchants travelled lands freely and the city had a huge fleet of merchant ships (known as argosy) that travelled all over the world.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] From these travels they founded some settlements, from India (cf.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] Ragusan trade with India) to America, and brought parts of their culture and flora home with them.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] One of its keys to success was not conquering, but trading and sailing under a white flag with the Latin: *Libertas* word (freedom) prominently featured on it.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] The flag was adopted when slave trading was abolished in 1418.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] In search of Indian spices and textiles, merchants from Dubrovnik arrived in Goa, India, and settled in what is now called Gandauli.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] The people of Dubrovnik arrived in the Portuguese colony of Goa between 1530 and 1535, and after that they founded their own colony, Sao Braz, named after the patron saint of Dubrovnik, St.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] The church was built around 1563 and was a replica of the original church of St.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] About 12,000 inhabitants lived in São Braz and was a thriving colony until the 1570s when trade between Croats and Indians declined.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] Many Conversos, Jews from Spain and Portugal who converted to Christianity, were attracted to the city.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] In May 1544, a ship landed there filled exclusively with Portuguese refugees, as Balthasar de Faria reported to King John.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] During this time one of the most famous cannon and bell founders of his time worked in the city: Ivan Rabljanin (also known as Magister Johannes Baptista Arbensis de la Tolle).
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] By 1571 Dubrovnik had sold its protection over some Christian settlements in other parts of the Ottoman Empire to France and Venice.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] At that time there was also a colony of Dubrovnik in Fes in Morocco.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] The bishop of Dubrovnik was a Cardinal protector in 1571, at that time there were only 16 other countries which had Cardinal protectors.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] Dubrovnik was a tributary state of the Ottoman Empire at one time.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] From this, they gained benefits such as access to the Black Sea, paid less customs duties (they however needed to make tribute payments) and had the diplomatic support of the Turks in trade disputes against the Venetians.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] This status also allowed increased trade with the inland regions through the Balkan overland trade which made merchants from Dubrovnik to build up a strong network unequaled with other Christian states.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] The Republic gradually declined due to a combination of a Mediterranean shipping crisis and the catastrophic earthquake of 1667 that killed over 5,000 citizens, levelled most of the public buildings and, consequently, negatively affected the well-being of the Republic.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] In 1699, the Republic was forced to sell two mainland patches of its territory to the Ottomans in order to avoid being caught in the clash with advancing Venetian forces.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] Today this strip of land belongs to Bosnia and Herzegovina and is that country's only direct access to the Adriatic.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] A highlight of Dubrovnik's diplomacy was the involvement in the American Revolution.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] On 27 May 1806, the forces of the Empire of France occupied the neutral Republic of Ragusa.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] Upon entering Ragusan territory without permission and approaching the capital, the French General Jacques Lauriston demanded that his troops be allowed to rest and be provided with food and drink in the city before continuing on to take possession of their holdings in the Bay of Kotor.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] However, this was a deception because as soon as they entered the city, they proceeded to occupy it in the name of Napoleon.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] Almost immediately after the beginning of the French occupation, Russian and Montenegrin troops entered Ragusan territory and began fighting the French army, raiding and pillaging everything along the way and culminating in a siege of the occupied city during which 3,000 cannonballs fell on it.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] In 1808 Marshal Marmont issued a proclamation abolishing the Republic of Ragusa and amalgamating its territory into the French Empire's client state, the Napoleonic Kingdom of Italy.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] Marmont claimed the newly created title of "Duke of Ragusa" (*Duc de Raguse*) and in 1810 Ragusa, together with Istria and Dalmatia, went to the newly created French Illyrian Provinces.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] After seven years of French occupation, encouraged by the desertion of French soldiers after the failed invasion of Russia and the reentry of Austria in the war, all the social classes of the Ragusan people rose up in a general insurrection, led by the patricians, against the Napoleonic invaders.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] On 18 June 1813, together with British forces they forced the surrender of the French garrison of the island of Šipan, soon also the heavily fortified town of Ston and the island of Lopud, after which the insurrection spread throughout the mainland, starting with Konavle.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] They then laid siege to the occupied city, helped by the British Royal Navy, who had enjoyed unopposed domination over the Adriatic sea, under the command of Captain William Hoste, with his ships HMS *Bacchante* and HMS *Saracen*.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] Soon the population inside the city joined the insurrection.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] The Austrian Empire sent a force under General Todor Milutinović offering to help their Ragusan allies.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] However, as was soon shown, their intention was to in fact replace the French occupation of Ragusa with their own.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] After this, the Flag of Saint Blaise was flown alongside the Austrian and British colors, but only for two days because, on 30 January, General Milutinović ordered Mayor Sabo Giorgi to lower it.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] Overwhelmed by a feeling of deep patriotic pride, Giorgi, the last Rector of the Republic, refused to do so "for the masses had hoisted it".
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] Subsequent events proved that Austria took every possible opportunity to invade the entire coast of the eastern Adriatic, from Venice to Kotor.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] The Austrians did everything in their power to eliminate the Ragusa issue at the Congress of Vienna.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] Ragusan representative Miho Bona, elected at the last meeting of the Major Council, was denied participation in the Congress, while Milutinović, prior to the final agreement of the allies, assumed complete control of the city.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] While many smaller and less significant cities and former countries were permitted an audience, that right was refused to the representative of the Ragusan Republic.
[src:e1-series-boat-racing/dubrovnik-p01] The official language until 1472 was Latin.
